# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] Human marrow produces approximately 500 billion blood cells per day, which join the systemic circulation via permeable vasculature sinusoids within the medullary cavity.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] All types of hematopoietic cells, including both myeloid and lymphoid lineages, are created in bone marrow; however, lymphoid cells must migrate to other lymphoid organs (e.g. thymus) in order to complete maturation.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] Bone marrow transplants can be conducted to treat severe diseases of the bone marrow, including certain forms of cancer such as leukemia.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] Several types of stem cells are related to bone marrow.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] Hematopoietic stem cells in the bone marrow can give rise to hematopoietic lineage cells, and mesenchymal stem cells, which can be isolated from the primary culture of bone marrow stroma, can give rise to bone, adipose, and cartilage tissue.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] The composition of marrow is dynamic, as the mixture of cellular and non-cellular components (connective tissue) shifts with age and in response to systemic factors.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] In humans, marrow is colloquially characterized as **red bone marrow**, or **yellow bone marrow** (Latin: *medulla ossium rubra* and *medulla ossium flava*, respectively) depending on the prevalence of hematopoietic cells vs fat cells.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] While the precise mechanisms underlying marrow regulation are not understood, compositional changes occur according to stereotypical patterns.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] For example, a newborn baby's bones exclusively contain hematopoietically active red marrow, and there is a progressive conversion towards yellow marrow with age.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] In adults, red marrow is found mainly in the central skeleton, such as the pelvis, sternum, cranium, ribs, vertebrae and scapulae, and variably found in the proximal epiphyseal ends of long bones such as the femur and humerus.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] In circumstances of chronic hypoxia, the body can convert yellow marrow back to red marrow to increase blood cell production.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] At the cellular level, the main functional component of bone marrow includes the progenitor cells which are destined to mature into blood and lymphoid cells.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] Human marrow produces approximately 500 billion blood cells per day.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] Marrow contains hematopoietic stem cells which give rise to the three classes of blood cells that are found in circulation: white blood cells (leukocytes), red blood cells (erythrocytes), and platelets (thrombocytes).
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] The stroma of the bone marrow includes all tissue not directly involved in its primary function of hematopoiesis.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] Stromal cells support hematopoiesis indirectly by providing a specialized microenvironment that influences the function and differentiation of hematopoietic cells.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] For example, they produce colony-stimulating factors, which play a significant role in regulating blood cell formation.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] That bone marrow is a priming site for T-cell responses to blood-borne antigens was first described in 2003.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] Mature circulating naïve T cells home to bone marrow sinuses after they have passed through arteries and arterioles.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] They transmigrate sinus endothelium and enter the parenchyma which contains dendritic cells (DCs).
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] These have a capacity of antigen uptake, processing, and presentation.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] Cognate interactions between antigen-specific T cells and antigen-presenting DCs (APCs) in parenchyma lead to rapid T-APC cluster formation followed by T cell activation, T cell proliferation and T cell re-circulation to blood.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] These findings were corroborated and extended in 2013 by in situ two-photon dynamic imaging of mice skulls.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] Bone marrow is a nest for migratory memory T cells and a sanctuary for plasma cells.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] This has implications for adaptive immunity and vaccinology.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] Memory B and T cells persist in the parenchyma in dedicated survival niches organized by stromal cells.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] This memory can be maintained over long time periods in the form of quiescent cells or by repeated antigenic restimulation.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] Bone marrow protects and optimizes immunological memory during dietary restriction.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] In cancer patients, cancer-reactive memory T cells can arise in bone marrow spontaneously or after specific vaccination.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] The bone marrow stroma contains mesenchymal stem cells (MSCs), which are also known as marrow stromal cells.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] These are multipotent stem cells that can differentiate into a variety of cell types.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] MSCs have been shown to differentiate, in vitro or in vivo, into osteoblasts, chondrocytes, myocytes, marrow adipocytes and beta-pancreatic islets cells.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] The blood vessels of the bone marrow constitute a barrier, inhibiting immature blood cells from leaving the marrow.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] Only mature blood cells contain the membrane proteins, such as aquaporin and glycophorin, that are required to attach to and pass the blood vessel endothelium.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] Hematopoietic stem cells may also cross the bone marrow barrier, and may thus be harvested from blood.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] The red bone marrow is a key element of the lymphatic system, being one of the primary lymphoid organs that generate lymphocytes from immature hematopoietic progenitor cells.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] The bone marrow and thymus constitute the primary lymphoid tissues involved in the production and early selection of lymphocytes.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] Furthermore, bone marrow performs a valve-like function to prevent the backflow of lymphatic fluid in the lymphatic system.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] Biological compartmentalization is evident within the bone marrow, in that certain cell types tend to aggregate in specific areas.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] For instance, erythrocytes, macrophages, and their precursors tend to gather around blood vessels, while granulocytes gather at the borders of the bone marrow.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] People have used animal bone-marrow in cuisine worldwide for millennia, as in the famed Milanese Ossobuco.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] The normal bone marrow architecture can be damaged or displaced by aplastic anemia, malignancies such as multiple myeloma, or infections such as tuberculosis, leading to a decrease in the production of blood cells and blood platelets.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] The bone marrow can also be affected by various forms of leukemia, which attacks its hematologic progenitor cells.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] Furthermore, exposure to radiation or chemotherapy will kill many of the rapidly dividing cells of the bone marrow, and will therefore result in a depressed immune system.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] Many of the symptoms of radiation poisoning are due to damage sustained by the bone marrow cells.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] To diagnose diseases involving the bone marrow, a bone marrow aspiration is sometimes performed.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] This typically involves using a hollow needle to acquire a sample of red bone marrow from the crest of the ilium under general or local anesthesia.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] Medical imaging may provide a limited amount of information regarding bone marrow.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] Plain film x-rays pass through soft tissues such as marrow and do not provide visualization, although any changes in the structure of the associated bone may be detected.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] CT imaging has somewhat better capacity for assessing the marrow cavity of bones, although with low sensitivity and specificity.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] For example, normal fatty "yellow" marrow in adult long bones is of low density (-30 to -100 Hounsfield units), between subcutaneous fat and soft tissue.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] Tissue with increased cellular composition, such as normal "red" marrow or cancer cells within the medullary cavity will measure variably higher in density.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] MRI is more sensitive and specific for assessing bone composition.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] MRI enables assessment of the average molecular composition of soft tissues and thus provides information regarding the relative fat content of marrow.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] In adult humans, "yellow" fatty marrow is the dominant tissue in bones, particularly in the (peripheral) appendicular skeleton.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] Because fat molecules have a high T1-relaxivity, T1-weighted imaging sequences show "yellow" fatty marrow as bright (hyperintense).
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] Furthermore, normal fatty marrow loses signal on fat-saturation sequences, in a similar pattern to subcutaneous fat.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] When "yellow" fatty marrow becomes replaced by tissue with more cellular composition, this change is apparent as decreased brightness on T1-weighted sequences.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] Both normal "red" marrow and pathologic marrow lesions (such as cancer) are darker than "yellow" marrow on T1-weight sequences, although can often be distinguished by comparison with the MR signal intensity of adjacent soft tissues.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] Normal "red" marrow is typically equivalent or brighter than skeletal muscle or intervertebral disc on T1-weighted sequences.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] Fatty marrow change, the inverse of red marrow hyperplasia, can occur with normal aging, though it can also be seen with certain treatments such as radiation therapy.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] Diffuse marrow T1 hypointensity without contrast enhancement or cortical discontinuity suggests red marrow conversion or myelofibrosis.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] Falsely normal marrow on T1 can be seen with diffuse multiple myeloma or leukemic infiltration when the water to fat ratio is not sufficiently altered, as may be seen with lower grade tumors or earlier in the disease process.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] Bone marrow examination is the pathologic analysis of samples of bone marrow obtained via biopsy and bone marrow aspiration.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] Bone marrow examination is used in the diagnosis of a number of conditions, including leukemia, multiple myeloma, anemia, and pancytopenia.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] The bone marrow produces the cellular elements of the blood, including platelets, red blood cells and white blood cells.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] While much information can be gleaned by testing the blood itself (drawn from a vein by phlebotomy), it is sometimes necessary to examine the source of the blood cells in the bone marrow to obtain more information on hematopoiesis; this is the role of bone marrow aspiration and biopsy.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] The ratio between myeloid series and erythroid cells is relevant to bone marrow function, and also to diseases of the bone marrow and peripheral blood, such as leukemia and anemia.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] The normal myeloid-to-erythroid ratio is around 3:1; this ratio may increase in myelogenous leukemias, decrease in polycythemias, and reverse in cases of thalassemia.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] In a bone marrow transplant, hematopoietic stem cells are removed from a person and infused into another person (allogeneic) or into the same person at a later time (autologous).
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] If the donor and recipient are compatible, these infused cells will then travel to the bone marrow and initiate blood cell production.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] Transplantation from one person to another is conducted for the treatment of severe bone marrow diseases, such as congenital defects, autoimmune diseases or malignancies.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] The patient's own marrow is first killed off with drugs or radiation, and then the new stem cells are introduced.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] Before radiation therapy or chemotherapy in cases of cancer, some of the patient's hematopoietic stem cells are sometimes harvested and later infused back when the therapy is finished to restore the immune system.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] Bone marrow stem cells can be induced to become neural cells to treat neurological illnesses, and can also potentially be used for the treatment of other illnesses, such as inflammatory bowel disease.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] In 2013, following a clinical trial, scientists proposed that bone marrow transplantation could be used to treat HIV in conjunction with antiretroviral drugs; however, it was later found that HIV remained in the bodies of the test subjects.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] The stem cells are typically harvested directly from the red marrow in the iliac crest, often under general anesthesia.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] The procedure is minimally invasive and does not require stitches afterwards.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] Depending on the donor's health and reaction to the procedure, the actual harvesting can be an outpatient procedure, or can require 1–2 days of recovery in the hospital.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] Another option is to administer certain drugs that stimulate the release of stem cells from the bone marrow into circulating blood.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] An intravenous catheter is inserted into the donor's arm, and the stem cells are then filtered out of the blood.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] This procedure is similar to that used in blood or platelet donation.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] In adults, bone marrow may also be taken from the sternum, while the tibia is often used when taking samples from infants.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] In newborns, stem cells may be retrieved from the umbilical cord.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] One of the most damaged areas of the body following chemotherapy is typically the uterus.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] Following uterine damage due to cancer treatment, follicle damage makes it difficult for individuals to get pregnant even if viable ova are present.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] With bone marrow stem cell transplants, chemotherapy patients have been able to increase their fertility as follicle damage is repaired.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] As follicles are necessary for ovum attachment to the endometrium, it is important for these areas to be repaired in order to increase fertility.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] For individuals who have sustained egg and follicle damage, IVF has been found to be more effective following bone marrow stem cell transplantation.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] One human clinical case has shown improvements of uterine lining thickness and overall endometrium repair following bone marrow stem cell transplantation.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] This repair allowed for the patient to successfully become pregnant and carry to term.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] Additional repairs following bone marrow stem cell transplant to the endometrium include increased vascularity and iron levels, with egg implantation clustering around areas with high blood flow.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] Using quantitative polymerase chain reaction (qPCR) and next-generation sequencing (NGS) a maximum of five DNA viruses per individual have been identified.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] Included were several herpesviruses, hepatitis B virus, Merkel cell polyomavirus, and human papillomavirus 31.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] Given the reactivation and/or oncogenic potential of these viruses, their repercussion on hematopoietic and malignant disorders calls for further studies.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] The earliest fossilised evidence of bone marrow was discovered in 2014 in *Eusthenopteron*, a lobe-finned fish which lived during the Devonian period approximately 370 million years ago.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] Scientists from Uppsala University and the European Synchrotron Radiation Facility used X-ray synchrotron microtomography to study the fossilised interior of the skeleton's humerus, finding organised tubular structures akin to modern vertebrate bone marrow.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/bone-marrow] *Eusthenopteron* is closely related to the early tetrapods, which ultimately evolved into the land-dwelling mammals and reptiles of the present day.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/children-s-hospice] A **Children's hospice** is a hospice specifically designed to help children and young people who are not expected to reach adulthood with the emotional and physical challenges they face, and also to provide respite care for their families.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/children-s-hospice] Children's hospice services work with families from all faiths, cultures and ethnic backgrounds and respect the importance of religious customs and cultural needs that are essential to the daily lives of each family.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/children-s-hospice] Many have a chaplain who is familiar with a variety of faiths and customs.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/children-s-hospice] Each service is typically an independent charity which relies on public support to continue their work.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/children-s-hospice] Children's hospice services are dedicated to improving the quality of life of children and young people who are not expected to live to reach adulthood and their families.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/children-s-hospice] They provide flexible, practical and free support at home and in the hospice to the entire family, often over many years and at any stage of the child's or young person's illness.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/children-s-hospice] This includes short breaks and daytime activities enabling families to get a rest; help with the control of pain or other distressing symptoms; and support for family members, including brothers and sisters.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/children-s-hospice] When the end of a child's life approaches, children's hospice services are there to provide end-of-life care and bereavement support for as long as it's needed, helping families and friends approach death with dignity and peace.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/children-s-hospice] Helen House in Oxfordshire was the world's first children's hospice.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/children-s-hospice] Helen House sprang from a friendship between Sister Frances Dominica and the parents of a seriously ill little girl called Helen, who lived at home with her family but required 24-hour care.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/children-s-hospice] The first children's hospice in Scotland Rachel House, run by Children's Hospice Association Scotland opened in March 1996.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/children-s-hospice] There are now over 40 operational children's hospice services open across the UK.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/children-s-hospice] Children's hospice services in England receive an average of 5% government funding and rely heavily on public donations.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/children-s-hospice] The children's hospice movement is still in a relatively early stage in the United States, where many of the functions of a children's hospice are provided by children's hospitals.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/children-s-hospice] In 1983, of the 1,400 hospices in the United States, only four were able to accept children.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/children-s-hospice] When physicians have to decide that a child can no longer be medically cured, along with the parents a decision is made to end care, keeping in mind the best interest of the child.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/children-s-hospice] When a decision between the parents and physicians cannot be reached, which is a very small percentage.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/children-s-hospice] The physicians are then not obligated to provide any therapy care that the doctors have not deemed necessary towards the care goals of the child.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/children-s-hospice] Most parents of the children that have serious development disorders actively share the end of life decision-making process.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/children-s-hospice] The main factors that parents take into consideration when making end-of-life care decisions are the importance to advocate for the best interest of their child.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/children-s-hospice] Also, the visible suffering, the remaining quality of life, and the child's will to survive is an influence.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/children-s-hospice] Through the efforts of CHI, most of the over 3,000 hospices in the U.S. will now consider accepting children.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/children-s-hospice] Also, approximately 450 programs have children-specific hospice, palliative, or home care services.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/children-s-hospice] Children's hospitals today have ethics consultation.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/children-s-hospice] Ethics consultation is a conference that is intended to help Patients, Staff and other resolve ethical concerns.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/children-s-hospice] It all begins with taking into consideration of the patient's ethical beliefs, families, and those professionals involved in the case.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/children-s-hospice] Different individuals tend to abide by different ethical beliefs and ethical dilemmas tend to rise out of the difference in values or the priority of those shared values.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/children-s-hospice] Additional Institutions that care for those patients have certain set of values.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/children-s-hospice] Some institutions are specialized in prioritizing patient care and others are devoted to research.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/children-s-hospice] Some Hospitals are public, others are private.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/children-s-hospice] Some serve their community and values can vary from community to community which can also cause disagreements.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/children-s-hospice] Institutions and hospitals also have value of their own that are written in their Mission Statement of the Institution.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/children-s-hospice] Ethic committees began in the late 1960s and early 1970s.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/children-s-hospice] The original purpose was to bring voices to conversations about ethically controversial clinical situations.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/children-s-hospice] The original voices brought to the table of discussion of ethic committees were Theologians, philosophers, social scientists, scholars in the humanities and other experts.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/children-s-hospice] Over the years ethics consultations have become more widely accepted.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/children-s-hospice] Most hospitals in the United States and across the world now have ethics committees and process for ethics consultation.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/children-s-hospice] In the early 1970s many experts realized that the medical education was not designed and physicians were not trained to deal with ethical issues associated with new technologies such as mechanical ventilation, dialysis and transplantation.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/children-s-hospice] Before the creation of such technology kidney failure was sure to be fatal, now physicians were starting to make choices about where, when, and how someone could die.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/children-s-hospice] One of the solutions was to invite theologians, philosophers and social scientist that would help physicians think and solve complicated ethical issues.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] End-of-life care is most commonly provided at home, in the hospital, or in a long-term care facility with care being provided by family members, nurses, social workers, physicians, and other support staff.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Facilities may also have palliative or hospice care teams that will provide end-of-life care services.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Decisions about end-of-life care are often informed by medical, financial and ethical considerations.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] In most developed countries, medical spending on people in the last twelve months of life makes up roughly 10% of total aggregate medical spending, while those in the last three years of life can cost up to 25%.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Advances in medical care since the mid-20th century have expanded the options available to extend life and highlighted the importance of ensuring that an individual's preferences and values for end-of-life care are honored.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Advanced care planning is the process by which a person of any age is able to provide their preferences and ensure that their future medical treatment aligns with their personal values and life goals.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] It is typically a process, with ongoing discussions about a patient's prognosis and conditions and conversations about medical dilemmas and options.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] A person will typically have these conversations with their healthcare providers and ultimately record their preferences in an advance healthcare directive.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] An advance healthcare directive is a legal document that either documents a person's decisions about desired treatment or indicates who a person has entrusted to make their care decisions for them.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] The two main types of advance directives are a living will and durable power of attorney for healthcare.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] A living will includes a person's decisions regarding their future care, most of which addresses resuscitation and life support.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Still, it may also cover their preferences regarding hospitalization, pain management, and specific treatments available.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] A living will typically takes effect when a person is terminally ill with a low probability of recovery.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] A durable power of attorney for healthcare allows a person to appoint another individual to make healthcare decisions for them under a specified set of circumstances.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Combined directives—such as the "Five Wishes"—that include components of both the living will, and durable power of attorney for healthcare are increasingly utilized.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Advanced care planning often includes preferences for CPR initiation, nutrition (e.g., tube feeding), as well as decisions about the use of machines to keep a person breathing or support their heart or kidneys.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Advance care planning can be a complex and intimidating change for ailing persons.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Often, when the person must make a significant change, they will undergo five stages of change: precontemplation, contemplation, preparation, action, and maintenance.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Many studies have reported benefits to persons who complete advanced care planning, specifically noting improved individual and surrogate satisfaction with communication and decreased clinician distress.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] However, there is a notable lack of empirical data about the outcome improvements people experience, as there are considerable discrepancies in what constitutes advanced care planning and heterogeneity in the outcomes measured.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Advance care planning remains an underutilized option tool.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Researchers have published data to support the use of new relationship-based and supported decision-making models that can increase the use and maximize the benefit of advance care planning.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] End-of-life care conversations are part of the treatment planning process for terminally ill individuals requiring palliative care, involving a discussion of an individual's prognosis, specification of care goals, and individualized treatment planning.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] A 2022 Cochrane review examined the effectiveness of interpersonal communication interventions in end-of-life care.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] There is evidence that individuals prioritize proper symptom management, avoidance of suffering, and care that aligns with ethical and cultural standards.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Specific conversations can include discussions about cardiopulmonary resuscitation (ideally occurring before the active dying phase as to not force the conversation during a medical crisis/emergency), place of death, organ donation, and cultural/religious traditions.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] As there are many factors involved in the end-of-life care decision-making process, the attitudes and perspectives of dying individuals and families may vary.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] For example, family members may differ over whether life extension or life quality is the primary goal of treatment.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] As it can be challenging for families in the grieving process to make timely decisions that respect the patient's wishes and values, having an established advanced care directive in place can prevent over-treatment, under-treatment, or further complications in treatment management.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Shared decision-making (SDM) is crucial to end-of-life care conversations between patients, families, and providers.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] SDM allows patients and providers to collaborate on their treatment plans and efforts to ensure the patient's voice is heard.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] This model fosters a collaborative conversation between healthcare providers and patients that focuses on the patient's goals and beliefs, with the provider's expertise and medical knowledge to formulate a co-developed care plan.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] For instance, a terminally ill patient may prioritize quality of life and seek to formulate an effective plan with their trusted provider.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Patients and families may also struggle to grasp the inevitability of death and the differing risks and effects of medical and non-medical interventions available for end-of-life care.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] People might avoid discussing their end-of-life care, and often, the timing and quality of these discussions can be poor.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] For example, conversations regarding end-of-life care between chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) patients and clinicians often occur when the person with COPD has advanced-stage disease, if at all.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] To prevent interventions that are not in accordance with the patient's wishes, end-of-life care conversations and advanced care directives can allow for the care they desire, as well as help prevent confusion and strain for family members.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Applying SDM aids in making sure patients and providers are on the same page about the patient's plans and goals to promote mutual respect and communication.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] It ensures that all parties involved have their needs and wishes met and respected.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] In the case of critically ill babies, parents can participate more in decision-making if they are presented with options to be discussed rather than recommendations by the doctor.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Utilizing this communication style also leads to less conflict with doctors and might help the parents cope better with the eventual outcomes.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Careful use of opioids is important to maintaining patient quality of life while avoiding overdoses.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] , terminal anguish, restlessness (e.g., thrashing, plucking, or twitching).
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Symptoms may also sometimes be alleviated by rehydration, which may reduce the effects of some toxic drug metabolites.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] While not apparently distressing for the patient, the association of this symptom with impending death can create fear and uncertainty for those at the bedside.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Rattle may not be controllable if caused by deeper fluid accumulation in the bronchi or the lungs, such as occurs with pneumonia or some tumors.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Sometimes levomepromazine is used as second-line to alleviate both agitation and of nausea and vomiting.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Patients become increasingly likely to experience breathlessness in the last days and weeks of their lives, which can be very distressing for both the patients themselves and their loved ones.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Low food intake and opioid use can lead to constipation, which can then result in agitation, pain, and delirium.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] and stool softeners are used to prevent constipation.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] In patients with constipation, the dose of laxatives will be increased to relieve symptoms.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] is approved to treat constipation due to opioid use.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Other symptoms that may occur, and may be mitigated to some extent, include cough, fatigue, fever, and in some cases bleeding.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] In some settings, such as the home or hospice, sublingual routes of administration may be used for most prescriptions and medications.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Another means of medication delivery, available for use when the oral route is compromised, is a specialized catheter designed to provide comfortable and discreet administration of ongoing medications via the rectal route.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] The catheter was developed to make rectal access more practical and provide a way to deliver and retain liquid formulations in the distal rectum so that health practitioners can leverage the established benefits of rectal administration.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Its small, flexible silicone shaft allows the device to be placed safely and remain comfortably in the rectum for repeated administration of medications or liquids.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] The catheter has a small lumen, allowing for small flush volumes to get medication to the rectum.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Integrated care pathways are an organizational tool used by healthcare professionals to clearly define the roles of each team member and coordinate how and when care will be provided.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] These pathways are utilized to ensure best practices for end-of-life care, such as evidence-based and accepted health care protocols, and to list the required care features for a specific diagnosis or clinical problem.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Many institutions have a predetermined pathway for end-of-life care, and clinicians should be aware of and use these plans when possible.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Integrated care pathways should also focus on standardizing healthcare processes while tailoring individual patient needs.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] For example, integrated pathways can be complex and promote a major change within the patient's lifestyle.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] In this case, it is essential to create a pathway that will allow an individual to maintain autonomy and their current lifestyle without making drastic changes.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] These factors can be evaluated from the Social Ecological Model.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] This model can be broken down into individual, interpersonal, organizational, community, and societal/ political factors.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] All of which can impact how an integrated pathway will be implemented.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] In the United Kingdom, end-of-life care pathways are based on the Liverpool Care Pathway.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Originally developed to provide evidence based care to dying cancer patients, this pathway has been adapted and used for a variety of chronic conditions at clinics in the UK and internationally.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] The BEACON Project group developed an integrated care pathway entitled the Comfort Care Order Set, which delineates care for the last days of life in either a hospice or acute care inpatient setting.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] The intervention did not, however, decrease the proportion of deaths that occurred in an ICU setting or the utilization of restraints around death.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] In cancer contexts, palliative care is intended to promote quality of life for the patient rather than cure disease, and can be provided as early as the point of diagnosis.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] End-of-life care is typically provided to patients with a life expectancy of less than a year.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Both care options target the comprehensive needs of patients, including the physical, emotional, social, and spiritual domains of suffering, with the goal of reducing suffering and improving quality of life.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] One systematic review found that many patients lack adequate understanding of the goals of palliative care.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Furthermore, the same review identified that clinicians may be hesitant to initiate conversations about prognosis in cases where outcomes are expected to be poor.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Research shows that high-quality end-of-life care involves a treatment plan that is oriented around the patient and emphasizes symptom management, respect for end-of-life preferences, and providing emotional and spiritual support.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Advance care planning and earlier end-of-life discussions between patient and clinician have been shown to promote quality of life and reduce the financial burden for the patient and their caregivers.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] One study advocates for the use of the biopsychosocial model when targeting pain as a symptom.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] In this model, the combination of medicinal and psychosocial interventions are utilized to better reduce suffering.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Other models involve interdisciplinary oncology teams that include nurses, social workers, and home-based care administration.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Additionally, they typically emphasize patient-clinician communication and psychosocial support, while also addressing the needs of both patient and primary caregiver.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Psychosocial treatments in cancer care consists of a variety of interventions that can be intended to help the patient with things like critical treatment decisions, reducing distress, contending with mortality, and improving overall mental and physical well-being.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] One review evaluated the ability of psychosocial interventions to reduce cancer-related fatigue (CRF), and found mindfulness and cognitive behavioral approaches to be among the most effective options evaluated.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] However, the review did not report any long-term impact from these therapies, and other research evaluating the benefits of psychosocial treatment on fatigue among adults with end-stage cancer who were receiving palliative care, found minor to no effects in fatigue-reduction among this population.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Research looking at psychosocial interventions on post-traumatic growth (PTG), found cognitive behavioral therapy and mindfulness-based therapies to produce the most optimal PTG outcomes among adult cancer patients.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] For the caregivers of cancer patients, research suggests that psychosocial interventions may improve feelings of caregiver burden, although effects faded after the intervention.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Beyond physical symptoms, psychosocial interventions show promise in improving feelings of meaning and purpose for cancer patients, although current research notes these improvements to be small to medium in effect size.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Still, continued beliefs of meaning or purpose may help individuals cope with distress and support their overall quality of life.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Research in cancer populations has shown that higher levels of meaning are linked to better psychological outcomes, including lower rates of depression, hopelessness, and anxiety, and have also been associated, to lesser extent, with improved physical well-being.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Maintaining a sense of meaning and purpose is particularly relevant in end-of-life cancer care, where psychological distress is common.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Overall, end-of-life care in oncology involves a combination of symptom management, psychosocial support, communication about care and treatment goals, and attention to the needs of the patient and their family.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Quality end-of-life care relies on coordination between care providers to best accommodate the different needs of each individual patient.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Lastly, honoring the preferences of the patient is critical in ensuring that end-of-life care aligns with their values and priorities as they approach the final stage of their illness.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] While not possible for every person needing care, surveys of the general public suggest most people would prefer to die at home.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] From 2003 to 2017, the number of deaths at home in the United States increased from 23.8% to 30.7%, while the number of deaths in the hospital decreased from 39.7% to 29.8%.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Home-based end-of-life care may be delivered in a number of ways, including by an extension of a primary care practice, by a palliative care practice, and by home care agencies such as Hospice.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] High-certainty evidence indicates that implementation of home-based end-of-life care programs increases the number of adults who will die at home and slightly improves their satisfaction at a one-month follow-up.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] There is low-certainty evidence that there may be very little or no difference in satisfaction of the person needing care for longer term (6 months).
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] The number of people admitted to the hospital during an end-of-life care program is unknown.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] In addition, the impact of home-based end-of-life care on caregivers, healthcare staff, and health service costs is not clear.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] However, there is weak evidence to suggest that this intervention may reduce health care costs by a small amount.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Not all groups in society have good access to end-of-life care.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] A systematic review conducted in 2021 investigated the end-of-life care experiences of people with severe mental illness, including those with schizophrenia, bipolar disorder, and major depressive disorder.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] The research found that individuals with a severe mental illness were unlikely to receive the most appropriate end-of-life care.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] The review recommended that there needs to be close partnerships and communication between mental health and end-of-life care systems, and these teams need to find ways to support people to die where they choose.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] More training, support, and supervision need to be available for professionals working in end-of-life care; this could also decrease prejudice and stigma against individuals with severe mental illness at the end of life, notably in those who are homeless.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] In addition, studies have shown that minority patients face several additional barriers to receiving quality end-of-life care.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Minority patients are prevented from accessing care at an equitable rate for a variety of reasons, including individual discrimination from caregivers, cultural insensitivity, racial economic disparities, as well as medical mistrust.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Many individuals with minority sexual and gender identities also experience disparities throughout illness and end-of-life care.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] One meta-analysis conducted in 2023 reported that LGBTQ+ individuals are disproportionately at greater risk for health issues, and that heteronormative and cisnormative assumptions within healthcare settings can lead to psychosocial or identity-related needs being overlooked.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Some LGBTQ+ patients reported feeling unsafe talking about their sexual and gender orientation.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Fear of discrimination and limited social support resources can further reduce access to equitable end-of-life care for these population groups.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Furthermore, these disparities can be understood through the Social Ecological Model.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] This model discusses how different factors, such as personal, environmental, political, and societal, influence a person's lifestyle.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] The model highlights how the different levels intersect and affect patients' ability to carry out their treatment plan.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Family members are often uncertain as to what they should be doing when a person is dying.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Many gentle, familiar daily tasks, such as combing hair, putting lotion on delicate skin, and holding hands, are comforting and provide a meaningful method of communicating love to a dying person.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Family members may be suffering emotionally due to the impending death.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Their own fear of death may affect their behavior.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] They may feel guilty about past events in their relationship with the dying person or feel that they have been neglectful.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] These common emotions can result in tension, fights between family members over decisions, worsened care, and sometimes (in what medical professionals call the "Daughter from California syndrome") a long-absent family member arrives while a patient is dying to demand inappropriately aggressive care.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Family involvement in end-of-life care can be both beneficial and detrimental to patients, depending on the shape that involvement takes.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] On the one hand, family involvement is associated with reduced patient distress when the goals of the patient and the family are convergent.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Loved ones can engage the patient in discussions about their care preferences, aid communication with the medical team, and offer social, emotional, and financial support.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] However, family involvement can also be detrimental when the goals of the patient and family are divergent.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Emotionally charged decision-making and differing opinions on medical decisions like terminal sedation, withdrawing of treatment, and transitioning to hospice can lead to arguments, conflict, and poor communication.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] End-of-life decisions can be explained by the Theory of Reasoned Action (TRA), which balances personal values and the opinions and beliefs of family members.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] In the context of end-of-life cancer care, some key themes regarding familial conflict at the end-of-life include patients and family members being on different pages regarding the illness prognosis, familial strife, cultural differences, and the general stress that accompanies caregiving.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] In addition to these, family can be a major predictor of whether or not the person engages in the behavior, and all parties have a mutual understanding of the end-of-life care plan.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Research on patient and family preferences have elucidated some key findings.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] In intensive care units, good communication, coordination between different arms of the care team, and spiritual support were found to be important to both patients and their families.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] When patients receive subpar end-of-life care – like recurring emergency room visits, chemotherapy administered at the end-of-life, or failure to be admitted to hospice – the well-being of their loved ones can suffer.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] In cases where the patient did not receive appropriate end-of-life care, families and loved ones experienced more depression and regret than families and loved ones with patients who experienced appropriate end-of-life care.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] However, this can also result in lapses of judgment, as physicians in these studies have typically showed intent to preserve a patient's "hope".
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] This brings up a whole different case on whether or not it is physician's jobs to promote "hope", but obviously it seems like most do try to.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Patients rely on their physician as an expert opinion, but in palliative care circumstances, the physician may want to involve the patient and their family more, since any medical interventions may be ineffective at that point.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] However, this again proves to be a slippery slope, as some patients facing existential uncertainty do not want a large part in the decision making process, instead defaulting to the previously mentioned expert opinion of doctors.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Research has indicated many physicians are ill-equipped with communication skills and training to assist them in end-of-life discussions.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] The study suggests that SDM in regards to palliative cancer care is a challenging and constantly evolving situation, with it mostly revolving around the relationship between the patient, the patient's family, and the physicians in charge.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Facilitating and building up the relationship between these parties is the best way to encourage positive SDM in palliative care cancer patients.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Spirituality is thought to be of increased importance to an individual's wellbeing during a terminal illness or toward the end-of-life.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] For example, most cancer patients report some level of spirituality or religiosity, but nearly half report some degree of spiritual struggle at the end-of-life.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Pastoral/spiritual care has a particular significance in end of life care, and is considered an essential part of palliative care by the WHO.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] In palliative care, responsibility for spiritual care is shared by the whole team, with leadership given by specialist practitioners such as pastoral care workers.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] The palliative care approach to spiritual care may, however, be transferred to other contexts and to individual practice.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Spiritual, cultural, and religious beliefs may influence or guide patient preferences regarding end-of-life care.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Healthcare providers caring for patients at the end of life can engage family members and encourage conversations about spiritual practices to better address the different needs of diverse patient populations.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Studies have shown that people who identify as religious also report higher levels of well-being.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] This leads to a higher level of self-efficacy and provides the person with the skills to make and execute decisions relating to end-of-life care.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Evidence supports that people who practice religion tend to have a more positive outlook on life and can help patients deal with stress associated with growing older.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] On the other hand religion has also been shown to be inversely correlated with depression and suicide.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] While religion provides some benefits to patients, there is some evidence of increased anxiety and other negative outcomes in some studies.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Religiosity, for example, has been associated with poorer advanced care planning.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Additionally, while spirituality has been associated with less aggressive end-of-life care, religion has been associated with an increased desire for aggressive care in some patients.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Despite these varied outcomes, spiritual and religious care remains an important aspect of care for patients.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Studies have shown that barriers to providing adequate spiritual and religious care include a lack of cultural understanding, limited time, and a lack of formal training or experience.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] There is nuance to the relationship between religiosity or spirituality and end-of-life care, because different trends emerge based on factors like religious denomination and geographical location.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] For example, Catholics are significantly less likely to have a do not resuscitate (DNR) order compared to non-Catholics.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Compared to Christians, Buddhists and Taoists in Singapore are more likely to receive aggressive, life-prolonging care.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] At the same time, people belonging to a particular religious or ethnic group should not be treated as a monolith.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Within these groups, beliefs and end-of-life care preferences can vary quite widely, highlighting the need for open-minded, adaptable, and culturally competent end-of-life care.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] In the Western world, many health care providers lack knowledge about culturally and spiritually informed end-of-life care and report discomfort when engaging in religious discussions with people whose beliefs differ from their own.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] This is one hypothesis as to why minorities access end-of-life care at lower rates than white people.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] At the same time, engagement with end-of-life care services can improve when clinicians are educated on culturally and spiritually diverse beliefs, which can foster better relationships and communication between health care providers, patients, and families.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Currently, web-based educational programs that center stories, dialogue, and personal reflection are showing promise at improving cultural and spiritual competence amongst providers.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Many hospitals, nursing homes, and hospice centers have chaplains who provide spiritual support and grief counseling to patients and families of all religious and cultural backgrounds.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] This review also highlighted how nurses who had difficulty giving care to their older patients perceived them as "weak, disabled, inflexible, and lacking cognitive or mental ability".
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Another systematic review considering structural and individual-level effects of ageism found that ageism led to significantly worse health outcomes in 95.5% of the studies and 74.0% of the 1,159 ageism-health associations examined.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Studies have also shown that one's own perception of aging and internalized ageism negatively impacts their health.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] In the same systematic review, they included this factor as part of their research.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] It was concluded that 93.4% of their total 142 associations about self-perceptions of aging show significant associations between ageism and worse health.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] End-of-life care is an interdisciplinary endeavor involving physicians, nurses, physical therapists, occupational therapists, pharmacists and social workers.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Depending on the facility and level of care needed, the composition of the interprofessional team can vary.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Health professional attitudes about end-of-life care depend in part on the provider's role in the care team.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Physicians generally have favorable attitudes towards Advance Directives, which are a key facet of end-of-life care.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Medical doctors who have more experience and training in end-of-life care are more likely to cite comfort in having end-of-life-care discussions with patients.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Those physicians who have more exposure to end-of-life care also have a higher likelihood of involving nurses in their decision-making process.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] A systematic review assessing end-of-life conversations between heart failure patients and healthcare professionals evaluated physician attitudes and preferences towards end-of-life care conversations.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Although physicians make official decisions about end-of-life care, nurses spend more time with patients and often know more about patient desires and concerns.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] In a Dutch national survey study of attitudes of nursing staff about involvement in medical end-of-life decisions, 64% of respondents thought patients preferred talking with nurses than physicians and 75% desired to be involved in end-of-life decision making.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] The ethics of end-of-life care revolve around dignity and respect for the patient by minimizing their suffering, enhancing their quality of life, and honoring any wishes or advance directives they may have put forth.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] In practice, however, these goals can be complicated by factors like patient competence, family influence, and the absence of advanced care planning.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Decisions about CPR, intubation, tube feeding, terminal sedation, physician-assisted suicide, and the stopping of life-prolonging treatment can all present ethical dilemmas for doctors and caregivers as they try to strike a balance between prolonging a patient's life and preventing unnecessary pain.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Confusion surrounding the difference between euthanasia and withdrawing or withholding treatment is a distinction that can be distressing for family members and doctors alike.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Not only can this conflict be unpleasant for doctors, it can also lead to poorer outcomes for patients.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] Thus, clear directives are needed to identify when it is acceptable to withdraw or withhold treatment at the end of life.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] One argument contends that there is no ethical distinction between stopping a life-prolonging medical intervention once it has begun, and refusing to start it all together.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p01] If the intervention is medically futile, contrary to the best interest of the patient, or unwanted by the patient (either in the moment or in an advance directive), then it is ethically acceptable to withdraw or withhold treatment.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p02] In 2012, Statistics Canada's *General Social Survey on Caregiving and care receiving* found that 13% of Canadians (3.7 million) aged 15 and older reported that at some point in their lives they had provided end-of-life or palliative care to a family member or friend.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p02] For those in their 50s and 60s, the percentage was higher, with about 20% reporting having provided palliative care to a family member or friend.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p02] Women were also more likely to have provided palliative care over their lifetimes, with 16% of women reporting having done so, compared with 10% of men.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p02] These caregivers helped terminally ill family members or friends with personal or medical care, food preparation, managing finances or providing transportation to and from medical appointments.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p02] End of life care has been identified by the UK Department of Health as an area where quality of care has previously been "very variable," and which has not had a high profile in the NHS and social care.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p02] To address this, a national end of life care programme was established in 2004 to identify and propagate best practice, and a national strategy document published in 2008.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p02] The Scottish Government has also published a national strategy.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p02] In 2006 just over half a million people died in England, about 99% of them adults over the age of 18, and almost two-thirds adults over the age of 75.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p02] About three-quarters of deaths could be considered "predictable" and followed a period of chronic illness – for example heart disease, cancer, stroke, or dementia.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p02] In all, 58% of deaths occurred in an NHS hospital, 18% at home, 17% in residential care homes (most commonly people over the age of 85), and about 4% in hospices.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p02] However, a majority of people would prefer to die at home or in a hospice, and according to one survey less than 5% would rather die in hospital.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p02] A key aim of the strategy therefore is to reduce the needs for dying patients to have to go to hospital and/or to have to stay there; and to improve provision for support and palliative care in the community to make this possible.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p02] One study estimated that 40% of the patients who had died in hospital had not had medical needs that required them to be there.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p02] In 2015 and 2010, the UK ranked highest globally in a study of end-of-life care.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p02] The 2015 National Institute for Health and Care Excellence guidelines introduced religion and spirituality among the factors which physicians shall take into account for assessing palliative care needs.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p02] In 2016, the UK Minister of Health signed a document which declared people "should have access to personalised care which focuses on the preferences, beliefs and spiritual needs of the individual." As of 2017, more than 47% of the 500,000 deaths in the UK occurred in hospitals.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p02] In 2021 the National Palliative and End of Life Care Partnership published their six ambitions for 2021–26.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p02] These include fair access to end of life care for everyone regardless of who they are, where they live or their circumstances, and the need to maximise comfort and wellbeing.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p02] Informed and timely conversations are also highlighted.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p02] Research funded by the UK's National Institute for Health and Care Research (NIHR) has addressed these areas of need.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p02] Examples highlight inequalities faced by several groups and offers recommendations.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p02] These include the need for close partnership between services caring for people with severe mental illness, improved understanding of barriers faced by Gypsy, Traveller and Roma communities, the provision of flexible palliative care services for children from ethnic minorities or deprived areas.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p02] Other research suggests that giving nurses and pharmacists easier access to electronic patient records about prescribing could help people manage their symptoms at home.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p02] A named professional to support and guide patients and carers through the healthcare system could also improve the experience of care at home at the end of life.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p02] A synthesised review looking at palliative care in the UK created a resource showing which services were available and grouped them according to their intended purpose and benefit to the patient.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p02] They also stated that currently in the UK palliative services are only available to patients with a timeline to death, usually 12 months or less.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p02] They found these timelines to often be inaccurate and created barriers to patients accessing appropriate services.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p02] They call for a more holistic approach to end of life care which is not restricted by arbitrary timelines.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p02] As of 2019, physician-assisted dying is legal in eight states (California, Colorado, Hawaii, Maine, New Jersey, Oregon, Vermont, Washington) and Washington D.C.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p02] Spending on those in the last twelve months accounts for 8.5% of total aggregate medical spending in the United States.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p02] When considering only those aged 65 and older, estimates show that about 27% of Medicare's annual $327 billion budget ($88 billion) in 2006 goes to care for patients in their final year of life.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p02] For the over-65s, between 1992 and 1996, spending on those in their last year of life represented 22% of all medical spending, 18% of all non-Medicare spending, and 25 percent of all Medicaid spending for the poor.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p02] These percentages appears to be falling over time, as in 2008, 16.8% of all medical spending on the over 65s went on those in their last year of life.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p02] Predicting death is difficult, which has affected estimates of spending in the last year of life; when controlling for spending on patients who were predicted as likely to die, Medicare spending was estimated at 5% of the total.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p02] Belgium's first palliative home care team was established in 1987, and the first palliative care unit and hospital care support teams were established in 1991.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p02] A strong legal and structural framework for palliative care was established in the 1990s, which divided the country into areas of 30, where palliative care networks were responsible for coordinating palliative services.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p02] Home care was provided by palliative support teams, and each hospital and care home recognized to have a palliative support team.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p02] In 1999, Belgium ranked second (after the United Kingdom) in the number of palliative care beds per capita.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p02] In 2001, there was an active palliative care support team in 72% of hospitals and a specialized nurse or active support team in 50% nursing homes.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p02] Government resources for palliative care doubled in 2000, and in 2007 Belgium was ranked third out of 52 countries worldwide in terms of resources for palliative care.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p02] (Together with the United Kingdom and Ireland) to raise public awareness under the auspices of EoL 6 According to the Lien Foundation report, Belgium ranks 5th (out of 40 countries worldwide) for the overall level of mortality.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p02] Palliative care services in Indonesia were first introduced in 1992 and formally incorporated into national health policy in 2007.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p02] Indonesia ranked 53rd out of 80 countries in the 2015 Quality of Death Index, reflecting relatively limited integration of end-of-life care into the healthcare system compared to global standards.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p02] As of 2026, access to end-of-life care remains highly unequal.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p02] Recent reviews indicate that palliative care services are still limited in availability and are not fully integrated into the national health system, with significant disparities between urban and rural areas.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p02] The burden of care is often shifted to families due to insufficient institutional support.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p02] In many cases, patients rely on informal caregiving at home, with substantial financial and emotional strain, and continued reliance on out-of-pocket payments or charitable assistance.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/end-of-life-care-p02] Assessments described palliative care services as being "in their infancy," with many patients lacking access to appropriate end-of-life care altogether.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] Hospice care in the United States is largely defined by the practices of the Medicare system and other health insurance providers, which cover inpatient or at-home hospice care for patients with terminal diseases who are estimated to live six months or less.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] Hospice care under the Medicare Hospice Benefit requires documentation from two physicians estimating a person has less than six months to live if the disease follows its usual course.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] Hospice benefits include access to a multidisciplinary treatment team specialized in end-of-life care and can be accessed in the home, long-term care facility or the hospital.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] Outside the United States, the term tends to be primarily associated with the particular buildings or institutions that specialize in such care.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] Such institutions may similarly provide care mostly in an end-of-life setting, but they may also be available for patients with other palliative care needs.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] Hospice care includes assistance for patients' families to help them cope with what is happening and provide care and support to keep the patient at home.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] The English word *hospice* is a borrowing from French.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] In France however, the word *hospice* refers more generally to an institution where sick and destitute people are cared for, and does not necessarily have a palliative connotation.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] The goal of hospice care is to prioritize comfort, quality of life and individual wishes.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] How comfort is defined is up to each individual or, if the patient is incapacitated, the patient's family.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] This can include addressing physical, emotional, spiritual and/or social needs.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] In hospice care, patient-directed goals are integral and interwoven throughout the care.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] Hospices typically do not perform treatments that are meant to diagnose or cure an illness but also do not include treatments that hasten death.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] Instead, hospices focus on palliative care to relieve pain and symptoms.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] This philosophy affects how hospice staff treat people and their families.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] Compared to general healthcare providers, hospice professionals take a different approach to talking to people and their families.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] They are more likely to make predictions or express uncertainty around future events (e.g., "He might die this week" or "I think she might live longer") than to issue orders or prescribe actions (e.g., "She needs a nurse" or "He can't go home").
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] The word *hospice* derives from Latin *hospitum*, meaning hospitality or place of rest and protection for the ill and weary.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] Historians believe the first hospices originated in Malta around 1065, dedicated to caring for the ill and dying en route to and from the Holy Land.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] The rise of the European Crusading movement in the 1090s placed the incurably ill into places dedicated to treatment.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] In the early 14th century, the order of the Knights Hospitaller of St.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] John of Jerusalem opened the first hospice in Rhodes.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] Hospices flourished in the Middle Ages, but languished as religious orders became dispersed.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] They were revived in the 17th century in France by the Daughters of Charity of Saint Vincent de Paul.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] France continued to see development in the hospice field; the hospice of L'Association des Dames du Calvaire, founded by Jeanne Garnier, opened in 1843.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] Six other hospices followed before 1900.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] Meanwhile, hospices developed in other areas.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] In the United Kingdom attention was drawn to the needs of the terminally ill in the middle of the 19th century, with *Lancet* and the *British Medical Journal* publishing articles pointing to the need of the impoverished terminally ill for good care and sanitary conditions.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] Steps were taken to remedy inadequate facilities with the opening of the Friedenheim in London, which by 1892 offered 35 beds to patients dying of tuberculosis.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] Four more hospices were established in London by 1905, including the Hostel of God on Clapham Common founded in 1891 by Clara Maria Hole, Mother Superior of Sisterhood of St James' (Anglican) and taken over in 1896 by the Society of Saint Margaret of East Grinstead.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] Australia, too, saw active hospice development, with notable hospices including the Home for Incurables in Adelaide (1879), the Home of Peace (1902) and the Anglican House of Peace for the Dying in Sydney (1907).
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] In 1899 New York City, the Servants for Relief of Incurable Cancer opened St.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] Rose's Hospice, which soon expanded to six locations in other cities.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] The more influential early developers of hospice included the Irish Religious Sisters of Charity, who opened Our Lady's Hospice in Harold's Cross, Dublin, Ireland, in 1879.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] It served as many as 20,000 people—primarily with tuberculosis and cancer—dying there between 1845 and 1945.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] The Sisters of Charity expanded internationally, opening the Sacred Heart Hospice for the Dying in Sydney in 1890, with hospices in Melbourne and New South Wales following in the 1930s.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] In 1905, they opened St Joseph's Hospice in London.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] In Western society, the concept of hospice began evolving in Europe in the 11th century.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] In Roman Catholic tradition, hospices were places of hospitality for the sick, wounded, or dying, as well as for travelers and pilgrims.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] The modern hospice concept includes palliative care for the incurably ill in institutions as hospitals and nursing homes, along with at-home care.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] The first modern hospice care was created by Dame Cicely Saunders in 1967.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] Saunders was a British registered nurse whose chronic health problems forced her to pursue a career in medical social work.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] The relationship she developed with a dying Polish refugee helped solidify her ideas that terminally ill patients needed compassionate care to help address their fears and concerns as well as palliative comfort for physical symptoms.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] After the refugee's death, Saunders began volunteering at St Luke's Home for the Dying Poor, where a physician told her that she could best influence the treatment of the terminally ill as a physician.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] Saunders entered medical school while continuing her volunteer work at St.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] When she completed her degree in 1957, she took a position there.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] Saunders emphasized focusing on the patient rather than the disease and introduced the notion of 'total pain', which included psychological and spiritual as well as physical discomfort.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] She experimented with opioids for controlling physical pain.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] She also considered the needs of the patient's family.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] She developed many foundational principles of modern hospice care at St Joseph's.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] She disseminated her philosophy internationally in a series of tours of the United States that began in 1963.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] In 1967, Saunders opened St Christopher's Hospice.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] Florence Wald, the dean of Yale School of Nursing, who had heard Saunders speak in America, spent a month working with Saunders there in 1969 before bringing the principles of modern hospice care back to the United States, establishing Hospice, Inc. in 1971.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] Another early hospice program in the United States, Alive Hospice, was founded in Nashville, Tennessee, on November 14, 1975.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] By 1977 the National Hospice Organization had been formed, and by 1979, a president, Ann G.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] Blues, had been elected and principles of hospice care had been addressed.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] Her 1969 best-seller, *On Death and Dying*, influenced the medical profession's response to the terminally ill.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] Balfour Mount introduced the concept of palliative care to Canada in the early 1970s and established the first hospice program at the Royal Victoria Hospital in Montreal, laying the foundation for modern palliative care practices.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] Saunders and other thanatology pioneers helped to focus attention on the types of care available to them.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] The IAHPC follows the philosophy that each country should develop a palliative care model based on its own resources and conditions.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] In 2006, the United States–based National Hospice and Palliative Care Organization (NHPCO) and the United Kingdom's Help the Hospices jointly commissioned an independent, international study of worldwide palliative care practices.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] Their survey found that 15% of the world's countries offered widespread palliative care services with integration into major health care institutions, while an additional 35% offered some form of palliative care services, in some cases localized or limited.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] As of 2009, an estimated 10,000 programs internationally provided palliative care, although the term hospice is not always employed to describe such services.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] In hospice care, the main guardians are the family care giver(s) and a hospice nurse/team who make periodic visits.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] Hospice can be administered in a nursing home, hospice building, or sometimes a hospital; however, it is most commonly practiced in the home.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] Hospice care targets the terminally ill who are expected to die within six months.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] Hospice was the subject of the Netflix 2018 Academy Award–nominated short documentary *End Game*, about terminally ill patients in a San Francisco hospital and Zen Hospice Project, featuring the work of palliative care physician BJ Miller and other palliative care clinicians.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] The film was executive produced by hospice and palliative care activist Shoshana R.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] The letter went viral after David Bowie's son Duncan Jones shared it.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] The letter was subsequently read out by the actor Benedict Cumberbatch and the singer Jarvis Cocker at public events.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] Hospice faced resistance from cultural and professional taboos against open communication about death among healthcare providers and the wider population, discomfort with unfamiliar medical techniques and perceived professional callousness towards the terminally ill.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] Nevertheless, the movement has spread throughout the world.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] A hospice opened in 1980 in Harare (Salisbury), Zimbabwe, the first in Sub-Saharan Africa.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] In spite of skepticism in the medical community, the hospice movement spread, and in 1987 the Hospice Palliative Care Association of South Africa formed.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] In 1990, Nairobi Hospice opened in Nairobi, Kenya.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] As of 2006, Kenya, South Africa and Uganda were among 35 countries offering widespread, well-integrated palliative care.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] Programs adopted the United Kingdom model, but emphasise home-based assistance.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] Following the foundation of hospice in Kenya in the early 1990s, palliative care spread throughout the country.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] Representatives of Nairobi Hospice sit on the committee to develop a Health Sector Strategic Plan for the Ministry of Health and work with the Ministry of Health to help develop palliative care guidelines for cervical cancer.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] The Government of Kenya supported hospice by donating land to Nairobi Hospice and providing funding to several of its nurses.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] In South Africa, hospice services are widespread, focusing on diverse communities (including orphans and homeless) and offered in diverse settings (including in-patient, day care and home care).
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] Over half of hospice patients in South Africa in the 2003–2004 year were diagnosed with AIDS, with the majority of the remaining diagnosed with cancer.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] Palliative care is supported by the Hospice Palliative Care Association of South Africa and by national programmes partly funded by the President's Emergency Plan for AIDS Relief.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] Hospice Africa Uganda (HAU), founded by Anne Merriman, began offering services in 1993 in a two-bedroom house loaned for the purpose by Nsambya Hospital.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] HAU has since expanded to a base of operations at Makindye, Kampala, with hospice services offered at roadside clinics by Mobile Hospice Mbarara since January 1998.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] That same year the Little Hospice Hoima opened in June.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] Hospice care in Uganda is supported by community volunteers and professionals, as Makerere University offers a distance diploma in palliative care.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] The government of Uganda published a strategic plan for palliative care that permits nurses and clinical officers from HAU to prescribe morphine.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] Canadian physician Balfour Mount, who first coined the term "palliative care", was a pioneer in medical research and in the Canadian hospice movement, which focused primarily on palliative care in a hospital setting.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] After meeting Kübler-Ross, Mount studied the experiences of the terminally ill at Royal Victoria Hospital, Montreal; the "abysmal inadequacy", as he termed it, that he found prompted him to spend a week with Cicely Saunders at St.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] Mount decided to adapt Saunders' model for Canada.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] Given differences in medical funding, he determined that a hospital-based approach would be more affordable, creating a specialized ward at Royal Victoria in January 1975.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] Canada's official languages include English and French, leading Mount to propose the term "palliative care ward", as the word *hospice* was already used in France to refer to nursing homes.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] Hundreds of palliative care programs then followed throughout Canada through the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] However, as of 2004, according to the Canadian Hospice Palliative Care Association (CHPCA), hospice palliative care was only available to 5–15% of Canadians, with government funding declining.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] At that time, Canadians were increasingly expressing a desire to die at home, but only two of Canada's ten provinces were provided medication cost coverage for home care.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] Only four of ten identified palliative care as a core health service.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] At that time, palliative care was not widely taught at nursing schools or universally certified at medical colleges; only 175 specialized palliative care physicians served all of Canada.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] Hospice in the United States has grown from a volunteer-led movement to improve care for people dying alone, isolated, or in hospitals, to a significant part of the health care system.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] In 2010, an estimated 1.581 million patients received hospice services.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] Hospice is the only Medicare benefit that includes pharmaceuticals, medical equipment, twenty-four-hour/seven-day-a-week access to care, and support for loved ones following a death.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] Hospice care is covered by Medicaid and most private insurance plans.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] Hospice care is available to people in home-like hospice residences, nursing homes, assisted living facilities, veterans' facilities, hospitals and prisons.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] Florence Wald, Dean of the Yale School of Nursing, founded one of the first hospices in the United States in New Haven, Connecticut, in 1974.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] The first hospital-based palliative care consultation service developed in the US was the Wayne State University School of Medicine in 1985 at Detroit Receiving Hospital.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] The first US-based palliative medicine and hospice service program was started in 1987 by Declan Walsh at the Cleveland Clinic Cancer Center in Cleveland, Ohio.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] Horvitz Center for Palliative Medicine, which was designated as a World Health Organization international demonstration project and accredited by the European Society of Medical Oncology as an Integrated Center of Oncology and Palliative Care.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] In 1982, Congress initiated the creation of the Medicare Hospice Benefit, which became permanent in 1986.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] In 1993, President Clinton installed hospice as a guaranteed benefit and an accepted component of health care provisions.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] As of 2017, 1.49 million Medicare beneficiaries were enrolled in hospice care for one day or more, which is a 4.5% increase from the previous year.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] From 2014 to 2019, Asian- and Hispanic-identifying beneficiaries of hospice care increased by 32% and 21% respectively.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] In 1879, the Religious Sisters of Charity opened Our Lady's Hospice in Dublin, Ireland.The first hospice to open in Great Britain was the Trinity Hospice in Clapham south London in 1891, on the initiative of the Hoare banking family.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] More than half a century later, a hospice movement developed after Dame Cicely Saunders opened St Christopher's Hospice in 1967, widely considered the first modern hospice.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] According to the UK's Help the Hospices, in 2011 UK hospice services consisted of 220 inpatient units for adults with 3,175 beds, 42 inpatient units for children with 334 beds, 288 home care services, 127 hospice at-home services, 272 day care services, and 343 hospital support services.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] These services together helped over 250,000 patients in 2003 and 2004.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] Funding varies from 100% funding by the National Health Service to almost 100% funding by charities, but the service is always free to patients.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] As of 2006, about 4% of all deaths in England and Wales occurred in a hospice setting (about 20,000 patients); a further number of patients spent time in a hospice, or were helped by hospice-based support services, but died elsewhere.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] Hospices also provide volunteering opportunities for over 100,000 people in the UK, whose economic value to the hospice movement has been estimated at over £112 million.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] According to the *Global Atlas of Palliative Care at the End of Life*, 78% of adults and 98% of children in need of palliative care at the end of life live in low and middle-income countries.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] Nevertheless, hospice and palliative care provision in Egypt is limited and sparsely available relative to the size of the population.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] Some of the obstacles to the development of these services have included the lack of public awareness, restricted availability of opioids, and the absence of a national hospice and palliative care development plan.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] Models of both home-based care and stand-alone hospices exist globally, but with the cultural and societal preferences of patients and their families to die at home in Egypt there is an inclination to focus on the development of home-based hospice and palliative care services.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] The first hospice unit in Israel opened in 1983.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] More than two decades later, a 2016 study found that 46% of the general Israeli public had never heard of it, despite the 70% of physicians who reported that they had the skill to treat patients according to palliative principles.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] Hospice care in Australia predated the opening of St Christophers in London by 79 years.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] The Irish Sisters of Charity opened hospices in Sydney (1889) and in Melbourne (1938).
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] The first hospice in New Zealand opened in 1979.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] Hospice care entered Poland in the mid-1970s.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] Japan opened its first hospice in 1981, officially hosting 160 by July 2006.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] India's first hospice, Shanti Avedna Ashram, opened in Bombay in 1986.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] The first hospice in the Nordics opened in Tampere, Finland in 1988.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] The first modern free-standing hospice in China opened in Shanghai in 1988.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] The first hospice unit in Taiwan, where the term for hospice translates as "peaceful care", opened in 1990.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] The first free-standing hospice in Hong Kong, where the term for hospice translates as "well-ending service", opened in 1992.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] The International Hospice Institute was founded in 1984.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] In 2006, the first World Hospice and Palliative Care Day was organised by the Worldwide Palliative Care Alliance, a network of hospice and palliative care national and regional organisations that support the development of hospice and palliative care worldwide.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] The event takes place on the second Saturday of October every year.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] Nurses that work in hospice in the home healthcare setting aim to relieve pain and holistically support their patient and the patient's family.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] Patients can receive hospice care when they have less than six months to live or would like to shift the focus of care from curative to comfort care.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] The goal of hospice care is to meet the needs of both the patient and family, knowing that a home death is not always the best outcome.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] Medicare covers all costs of hospice treatment.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] The hospice home health nurse must be skilled in both physical care and psychosocial care.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] Most nurses will work with a team that includes a physician, social worker and possibly a spiritual care counselor.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] Some of the nurse's duties will include reassuring family members, and ensuring adequate pain control.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] The nurse will need to explain to the patient and family that a pain-free death is possible, and scheduled opioid pain medications are appropriate in this case.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] The nurse will need to work closely with the medical provider to ensure that dosing is appropriate, and in the case of tolerance, the dose is raised.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] The nurse should be aware of cultural differences and needs and should aim to meet them.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospice] The nurse will also support the family after death and connect the family to bereavement services.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] A **hospital** is a healthcare institution providing patient treatment with specialized medical science and auxiliary healthcare staff and medical equipment.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] The best-known type of hospital is the **general hospital**, which typically has an emergency department to treat urgent health problems ranging from fire and accident victims to a sudden illness.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] A **district hospital** typically is the major health care facility in its region, with many beds for intensive care and additional beds for patients who need long-term care.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] Specialized hospitals include trauma centers, rehabilitation hospitals, children's hospitals, geriatric hospitals, and hospitals for specific medical needs, such as psychiatric hospitals for psychiatric treatment and other disease-specific categories.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] Specialized hospitals can help reduce health care costs compared to general hospitals.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] Hospitals are classified as general, specialty, or government depending on the sources of income received.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] A teaching hospital campus combines patient care with teaching to health science students, auxiliary healthcare students, and qualified medical graduates completing their postgraduate residencies before licensure to practice.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] A health science facility smaller than a hospital is generally called a clinic.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] Hospitals have a range of departments (e.g. surgery and urgent care) and specialist units such as cardiology.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] Some hospitals have outpatient departments and some have chronic treatment units.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] Common support units include a pharmacy, pathology, and radiology.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] Facilities that combine many health care functions, including general or specialized patient care, teaching, research, and so on, may use the term medical center.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] This term can also refer to an office complex with various unaffiliated health services or any kind of clinic or hospital.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] A large hospital or medical center also often serves as the administrative headquarters of a larger health system which may have multiple sites.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] Hospitals are typically funded by public funding, health organizations (for-profit or nonprofit), health insurance companies, or charities, including direct charitable donations.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] Historically, hospitals were often founded and funded by Christian religious orders, or by charitable individuals and leaders.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] Hospitals are currently staffed by professional physicians, surgeons, nurses, and allied health professionals.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] In the past, however, this work was usually performed by the members of founding religious orders or by volunteers.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] However, there are various Catholic religious orders, such as the Alexians and the Bon Secours Sisters that still focus on hospital ministry in the late 1990s, as well as several other Christian denominations, including the Evangelical-Lutherans and Methodists, which run hospitals.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] Deaconesses have played a prominent role in healthcare.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] In accordance with the original meaning of the word, hospitals were original "places of hospitality", and this meaning is still preserved in the names of some institutions such as the Royal Hospital Chelsea, established in 1681 as a retirement and nursing home for veteran soldiers.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] During the Middle Ages, hospitals served different functions from modern institutions in that they were almshouses for the poor, hostels for pilgrims, or hospital schools.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] The word "hospital" comes from the Latin *hospes*, signifying a stranger or foreigner, hence a guest.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] Another noun derived from this, *hospitium* came to signify hospitality, that is the relation between guest and shelterer, hospitality, friendliness, and hospitable reception.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] By metonymy, the Latin word then came to mean a guest-chamber, guest's lodging, an inn.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] *Hospes* is thus the root for the English words *host* (where the *p* was dropped for convenience of pronunciation) *hospitality*, *hospice*, *hostel,* and *hotel*.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] The latter modern word derives from Latin via the Old French romance word *hostel*, which developed a silent *s*, which letter was eventually removed from the word, the loss of which is signified by a circumflex in the modern French word *hôtel*.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] The German word *Spital* shares similar roots.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] Some patients go to a hospital just for diagnosis, treatment, or therapy and then leave ("outpatients") without staying overnight; while others are "admitted" and stay overnight or for several days or weeks or months ("inpatients").
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] Hospitals are usually distinguished from other types of medical facilities by their ability to admit and care for inpatients whilst the others, which are smaller, are often described as clinics.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] The best-known type of hospital is the general hospital, also known as an acute-care hospital.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] These facilities handle many kinds of disease and injury, and normally have an emergency department (sometimes known as "accident & emergency") or trauma center to deal with immediate and urgent threats to health.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] Larger cities may have several hospitals of varying sizes and facilities.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] Some hospitals, especially in the United States and Canada, have their own ambulance service.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] A district hospital typically is the major health care facility in its region, with large numbers of beds for intensive care, critical care, and long-term care.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] In California, "district hospital" refers specifically to a class of healthcare facility created shortly after World War II to address a shortage of hospital beds in many local communities.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] Even today, district hospitals are the sole public hospitals in 19 of California's counties, and are the sole locally accessible hospital within nine additional counties in which one or more other hospitals are present at a substantial distance from a local community.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] Twenty-eight of California's rural hospitals and 20 of its critical-access hospitals are district hospitals.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] They are formed by local municipalities, have boards that are individually elected by their local communities, and exist to serve local needs.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] They are a particularly important provider of healthcare to uninsured patients and patients with Medi-Cal (which is California's Medicaid program, serving low-income persons, some senior citizens, persons with disabilities, children in foster care, and pregnant women).
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] In 2012, district hospitals provided $54 million in uncompensated care in California.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] A specialty hospital is primarily and exclusively dedicated to one or a few related medical specialties.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] In Germany, specialised hospitals are called *Fachkrankenhaus*; an example is Fachkrankenhaus Coswig (thoracic surgery).
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] In India, specialty hospitals are known as *super-specialty hospitals* and are distinguished from multispecialty hospitals which are composed of several specialties.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] Specialised hospitals can help reduce health care costs compared to general hospitals.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] For example, Narayana Health's cardiac unit in Bangalore specialises in cardiac surgery and allows for a significantly greater number of patients.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] It has 3,000 beds and performs 3,000 paediatric cardiac operations annually, the largest number in the world for such a facility.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] Surgeons are paid on a fixed salary instead of per operation, thus when the number of procedures increases, the hospital is able to take advantage of economies of scale and reduce its cost per procedure.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] Each specialist may also become more efficient by working on one procedure like a production line.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] A teaching hospital delivers healthcare to patients as well as training to prospective medical professionals such as medical students and student nurses.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] It may be linked to a medical school or nursing school, and may be involved in medical research.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] Students may also observe clinical work in the hospital.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] Clinics generally provide only outpatient services, but some may have a few inpatient beds and a limited range of services that may otherwise be found in typical hospitals.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] A hospital contains one or more wards that house hospital beds for inpatients.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] It may also have acute services such as an emergency department, operating theatre, and intensive care unit, as well as a range of medical specialty departments.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] A well-equipped hospital may be classified as a trauma center.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] They may also have other services such as a hospital pharmacy, radiology, pathology, and medical laboratories.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] Some hospitals have outpatient departments such as behavioral health services, dentistry, and rehabilitation services.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] Freestanding emergency departments are often associated with a hospital, but are located away from the hospital with the intention of providing greater emergency service coverage to a region.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] A hospital may also have a department of nursing, headed by a chief nursing officer or director of nursing.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] This department is responsible for the administration of professional nursing practice, research, and policy for the hospital.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] Many units have both a nursing and a medical director that serve as administrators for their respective disciplines within that unit.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] For example, within an intensive care nursery, a medical director is responsible for physicians and medical care, while the nursing manager is responsible for all the nurses and nursing care.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] Support units may include a medical records department, release of information department, technical support, clinical engineering, facilities management, plant operations, dining services, and security departments.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] The COVID-19 pandemic stimulated the development of virtual wards across the British NHS.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] Patients are managed at home, monitoring their own oxygen levels using an oxygen saturation probe if necessary and supported by telephone.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] West Hertfordshire Hospitals NHS Trust managed around 1200 patients at home between March and June 2020 and planned to continue the system after COVID-19, initially for respiratory patients.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] Mersey Care NHS Foundation Trust started a COVID Oximetry@Home service in April 2020.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] This enables them to monitor more than 5000 patients a day in their own homes.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] The technology allows nurses, carers, or patients to record and monitor vital signs such as blood oxygen levels.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] In early India, Fa Xian, a Chinese Buddhist monk who travelled across India c.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] AD 400, recorded examples of healing institutions.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] According to the *Mahavamsa*, the ancient chronicle of Sinhalese royalty, written in the sixth century AD, King Pandukabhaya of Sri Lanka (r.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] 437–367 BC) had lying-in-homes and hospitals (Sivikasotthi-Sala).
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] A hospital and medical training center also existed at Gundeshapur, a major city in southwest of the Sassanid Persian Empire founded in AD 271 by Shapur I.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] In ancient Greece, temples dedicated to the healer-god Asclepius, known as Asclepeion functioned as centers of medical advice, prognosis, and healing.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] The Asclepeia spread to the Roman Empire.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] While public healthcare was non-existent in the Roman Empire, military hospitals called *valetudinaria* did exist stationed in military barracks and would serve the soldiers and slaves within the fort.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] Evidence exists that some civilian hospitals, while unavailable to the Roman population, were occasionally privately built in extremely wealthy Roman households located in the countryside for that family, although this practice seems to have ended in 80 AD.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] The declaration of Christianity as an accepted religion in the Roman Empire drove an expansion of the provision of care.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] Following the First Council of Nicaea in AD 325 construction of a hospital in every cathedral town was begun, including among the earliest hospitals by Saint Sampson in Constantinople and by Basil, bishop of Caesarea in modern-day Turkey.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] By the twelfth century, Constantinople had two well-organised hospitals, staffed by doctors who were both male and female.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] Facilities included systematic treatment procedures and specialised wards for various diseases.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] The earliest general hospital in the Islamic world was built in 805 in Baghdad by Harun Al-Rashid.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] By the 10th century, Baghdad had five more hospitals, while Damascus had six hospitals by the 15th century, and Córdoba alone had 50 major hospitals, many exclusively for the military, by the end of the 15th century.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] The Islamic bimaristan served as a center of medical treatment, as well nursing home and lunatic asylum.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] It typically treated the poor, as the rich would have been treated in their own homes.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] Hospitals in this era were the first to require medical licenses for doctors, and compensation for negligence could be made.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] Hospitals were forbidden by law to turn away patients who were unable to pay.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] These hospitals were financially supported by waqfs, as well as state funds.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] In India, public hospitals existed at least since the reign of Firuz Shah Tughlaq in the 14th century.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] The Mughal emperor Jahangir in the 17th century established hospitals in large cities at government expense with records showing salaries and grants for medicine being paid for by the government.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] In China, during the Song dynasty, the state began to take on social welfare functions previously provided by Buddhist monasteries and instituted public hospitals, hospices and dispensaries.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] In Europe the medieval concept of Christian care evolved during the 16th and 17th centuries into a secular one.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] In 1682, Charles II founded the Royal Hospital Chelsea as a retirement home for old soldiers known as Chelsea Pensioners, an instance of the use of the word "hospital" to mean an almshouse.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] Ten years later, Mary II founded the Royal Hospital for Seamen, Greenwich, with the same purpose.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] The voluntary hospital movement began in the early 18th century, with hospitals being founded in London by the 1720s, including Westminster Hospital (1719) promoted by the private bank C.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] Hoare & Co and Guy's Hospital (1724) funded from the bequest of the wealthy merchant, Thomas Guy.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] Other hospitals sprang up in London and other British cities over the century, many paid for by private subscriptions.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] St Bartholomew's in London was rebuilt from 1730 to 1759, and the London Hospital, Whitechapel, opened in 1752.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] These hospitals represented a turning point in the function of the institution; they began to evolve from being basic places of care for the sick to becoming centers of medical innovation and discovery and the principal place for the education and training of prospective practitioners.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] Some of the era's greatest surgeons and doctors worked and passed on their knowledge at the hospitals.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] They also changed from being mere homes of refuge to being complex institutions for the provision and advancement of medicine and care for sick.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] The Charité was founded in Berlin in 1710 by King Frederick I of Prussia as a response to an outbreak of plague.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] When the Vienna General Hospital opened in 1784 as the world's largest hospital, physicians acquired a new facility that gradually developed into one of the most important research centers.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] Another Enlightenment era charitable innovation was the dispensary; these would issue the poor with medicines free of charge.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] The London Dispensary opened its doors in 1696 as the first such clinic in the British Empire.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] The idea was slow to catch on until the 1770s, when many such organisations began to appear, including the Public Dispensary of Edinburgh (1776), the Metropolitan Dispensary and Charitable Fund (1779) and the Finsbury Dispensary (1780).
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] Dispensaries were also opened in New York 1771, Philadelphia 1786, and Boston 1796.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] The Royal Naval Hospital, Stonehouse, Plymouth, was a pioneer of hospital design in having "pavilions" to minimize the spread of infection.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] John Wesley visited in 1785, and commented "I never saw anything of the kind so complete; every part is so convenient, and so admirably neat.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] But there is nothing superfluous, and nothing purely ornamented, either within or without." This revolutionary design was made more widely known by John Howard, the philanthropist.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] In 1787 the French government sent two scholar administrators, Coulomb and Tenon, who had visited most of the hospitals in Europe.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] They were impressed and the "pavilion" design was copied in France and throughout Europe.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] English physician Thomas Percival (1740–1804) wrote a comprehensive system of medical conduct, *Medical Ethics; or, a Code of Institutes and Precepts, Adapted to the Professional Conduct of Physicians and Surgeons* (1803) that set the standard for many textbooks.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] In the mid-19th century, hospitals and the medical profession became more professionalised, with a reorganisation of hospital management along more bureaucratic and administrative lines.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] The Apothecaries Act 1815 made it compulsory for medical students to practise for at least half a year at a hospital as part of their training.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] Florence Nightingale pioneered the modern profession of nursing during the Crimean War when she set an example of compassion, commitment to patient care and diligent and thoughtful hospital administration.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] The first official nurses' training programme, the Nightingale School for Nurses, was opened in 1860, with the mission of training nurses to work in hospitals, to work with the poor and to teach.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] Nightingale was instrumental in reforming the nature of the hospital, by improving sanitation standards and changing the image of the hospital from a place the sick would go to die, to an institution devoted to recuperation and healing.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] She also emphasised the importance of statistical measurement for determining the success rate of a given intervention and pushed for administrative reform at hospitals.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] By the late 19th century, the modern hospital was beginning to take shape with a proliferation of a variety of public and private hospital systems.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] By the 1870s, hospitals had more than trebled their original average intake of 3,000 patients.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] In continental Europe the new hospitals generally were built and run from public funds.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] The National Health Service, the principal provider of health care in the United Kingdom, was founded in 1948.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] During the nineteenth century, the Second Viennese Medical School emerged with the contributions of physicians such as Carl Freiherr von Rokitansky, Josef Škoda, Ferdinand Ritter von Hebra, and Ignaz Philipp Semmelweis.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] Basic medical science expanded and specialisation advanced.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] Furthermore, the first dermatology, eye, as well as ear, nose, and throat clinics in the world were founded in Vienna, being considered as the birth of specialised medicine.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] By the late 19th and early 20th centuries, medical advancements such as anesthesia and sterile techniques that could make surgery less risky, and the availability of more advanced diagnostic devices such as X-rays, continued to make hospitals a more attractive option for treatment.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] Modern hospitals measure various efficiency metrics such as occupancy rates, the average length of stay, time to service, patient satisfaction, physician performance, patient readmission rate, inpatient mortality rate, and case mix index.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] In the United States, the number of hospitalizations grew to its peak in 1981 with 171 admissions per 1,000 Americans and 6,933 hospitals.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] This trend subsequently reversed, with the rate of hospitalization falling by more than 10% and the number of US hospitals shrinking from 6,933 in 1981 to 5,534 in 2016.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] Occupancy rates also dropped from 77% in 1980 to 60% in 2013.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] Among the reasons for this are the increasing availability of more complex care elsewhere such as at home or the physicians' offices and also the less therapeutic and more life-threatening image of the hospitals in the eyes of the public.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] In the US, a patient may sleep in a hospital bed, but be considered outpatient and "under observation" if not formally admitted.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] In the U.S., inpatient stays are covered under Medicare Part A, but a hospital might keep a patient under observation which is only covered under Medicare Part B, and subjects the patient to additional coinsurance costs.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] In 2013, the Centers for Medicare & Medicaid Services (CMS) introduced a "two-midnight" rule for inpatient admissions, intended to reduce an increasing number of long-term "observation" stays being used for reimbursement.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] In 2016 and 2017, healthcare reform and a continued decline in admissions resulted in US hospital-based healthcare systems performing poorly financially.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] Microhospitals, with bed capacities of between eight and fifty, are expanding in the United States.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] Similarly, freestanding emergency rooms, which transfer patients that require inpatient care to hospitals, were popularised in the 1970s and have since expanded rapidly across the United States.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] The Catholic Church is the largest non-government provider of health care services in the world.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] It has around 18,000 clinics, 16,000 homes for the elderly and those with special needs, and 5,500 hospitals, with 65 percent of them located in developing countries.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] In 2010, the Church's Pontifical Council for the Pastoral Care of Health Care Workers said that the Church manages 26% of the world's health care facilities.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] Modern hospitals derive funding from a variety of sources.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] They may be funded by private payment and health insurance or public expenditure, charitable donations.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] In the United Kingdom, the National Health Service delivers health care to legal residents funded by the state "free at the point of delivery", and emergency care free to anyone regardless of nationality or status.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] Due to the need for hospitals to prioritise their limited resources, there is a tendency in countries with such systems for 'waiting lists' for non-crucial treatment, so those who can afford it may take out private health care to access treatment more quickly.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] In the United States, hospitals typically operate privately and in some cases on a for-profit basis, such as HCA Healthcare.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] The list of procedures and their prices are billed with a chargemaster; however, these prices may be lower for health care obtained within healthcare networks.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] Legislation requires hospitals to provide care to patients in life-threatening emergency situations regardless of the patient's ability to pay.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] Privately funded hospitals which admit uninsured patients in emergency situations incur direct financial losses, such as in the aftermath of Hurricane Katrina.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] As the quality of health care has increasingly become an issue around the world, hospitals have increasingly had to pay serious attention to this matter.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] Independent external assessment of quality is one of the most powerful ways to assess this aspect of health care, and hospital accreditation is one means by which this is achieved.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] In England, hospitals are monitored by the Care Quality Commission.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] The World Health Organization reported in 2011 that being admitted to a hospital was far riskier than flying.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] Globally, the chance of a patient being subject to a treatment error in a hospital was about 10%, and the chance of death resulting from an error was about one in 300.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] 7% of hospitalised patients in developed countries, and 10% in developing countries, acquire at least one health care-associated infection.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] In the U.S., 1.7 million infections are acquired in hospital each year, leading to 100,000 deaths, figures much worse than in Europe where there were 4.5 million infections and 37,000 deaths.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] Modern hospital buildings are designed to minimise the effort of medical personnel and the possibility of contamination while maximising the efficiency of the whole system.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] Travel time for personnel within the hospital and the transportation of patients between units is facilitated and minimised.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] The building also should be built to accommodate heavy departments such as radiology and operating rooms while space for special wiring, plumbing, and waste disposal must be allowed for in the design.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] However, many hospitals, even those considered "modern", are the product of continual and often badly managed growth over decades or even centuries, with utilitarian new sections added on as needs and finances dictate.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] Some newer hospitals now try to re-establish design that takes the patient's psychological needs into account, such as providing more fresh air, better views and more pleasant colour schemes.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] These ideas harken back to the late eighteenth century, when the concept of providing fresh air and access to the 'healing powers of nature' were first employed by hospital architects in improving their buildings.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] The research of British Medical Association is showing that good hospital design can reduce patient's recovery time.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] Exposure to daylight is effective in reducing depression.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] Single-sex accommodation help ensure that patients are treated in privacy and with dignity.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] Exposure to nature and hospital gardens is also important – looking out windows improves patients' moods and reduces blood pressure and stress level.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] Open windows in patient rooms have also demonstrated some evidence of beneficial outcomes by improving airflow and increased microbial diversity.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] Eliminating long corridors can reduce nurses' fatigue and stress.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] Another ongoing major development is the change from a ward-based system (where patients are accommodated in communal rooms, separated by movable partitions) to one in which they are accommodated in individual rooms.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] The ward-based system has been described as very efficient, especially for the medical staff, but is considered to be more stressful for patients and detrimental to their privacy.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/hospital] A major constraint on providing all patients with their own rooms is however found in the higher cost of building and operating such a hospital; this causes some hospitals to charge for private rooms.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicester-royal-infirmary] The **Leicester Royal Infirmary** (LRI) is a National Health Service teaching hospital in Leicester, England.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicester-royal-infirmary] It is located to the south-west of the city centre.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicester-royal-infirmary] It has an accident and emergency department, women's hospital, paediatrics, oncology (including radiotherapy) and other specialisms.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicester-royal-infirmary] The infirmary is the largest of the three Leicester hospitals managed by the University Hospitals of Leicester NHS Trust.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicester-royal-infirmary] Parts of Leicester Medical School are based on the site.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicester-royal-infirmary] The hospital was founded by Reverend William Watts as the Leicester Infirmary with 40 beds in 1771.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicester-royal-infirmary] Patients were forced to pay a deposit when they went in; if they went home, the money was repaid; if they died their deposit would be spent on burying them.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicester-royal-infirmary] When first opened, there was no running water, but it did have its own brewery, from which beer was used to treat the patients.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicester-royal-infirmary] By 1808, the infirmary had expanded by 20 beds, to a total of 60 beds.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicester-royal-infirmary] A fever house opened at the infirmary in 1820 and nurses were first trained there in 1870.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicester-royal-infirmary] St Luke's Chapel, which benefited from extensive stained glass windows and memorials, was built in 1887.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicester-royal-infirmary] The facility became Leicester Infirmary and Children's Hospital in 1911 and Leicester Royal Infirmary and Children's Hospital in 1914 before it joined the National Health Service in 1948.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicester-royal-infirmary] The Windsor building was opened by the Queen in December 1993 and a new accident and emergency department was opened by the Princess Royal in March 2018.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicester-royal-infirmary] Hadiza Bawa-Garba, a junior doctor at the Infirmary, was convicted of manslaughter for her part in the death of a 6-year-old boy from sepsis and received a suspended prison sentence in 2015.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicester-royal-infirmary] Although the General Medical Council ruled in January 2018 that she be struck off the medical register, the Court of Appeal decided in August 2018 that she should be re-instated.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicester-royal-infirmary] A congenital heart centre opened at the Kensington Building at the Leicester Royal Infirmary in August 2021.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicester-royal-infirmary] This unit, which was transferred from Glenfield Hospital with support from Pick Everard, forms part of the East Midlands Congenital Heart Network.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicester-royal-infirmary] The Infirmary is the home of the East Midlands Forensic Pathology Unit, which provides the Home Office registered forensic pathology services to the police forces of Derbyshire, Leicestershire (and Rutland), Lincolnshire, Nottinghamshire and Northamptonshire.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] The county has an area of 2,156 km2 (832 sq mi) and an estimated population of 1,133,921 in 2024.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Leicester is in the centre of the county and is by far the largest settlement; its urban area includes the towns of Wigston and Oadby immediately to the south-east.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] The rest of the county is largely rural, and its settlements include the university town of Loughborough in the north, Melton Mowbray in the north-east, Hinckley in the south-west, Market Harborough in the south-east, and Coalville in the north-west.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] For local government purposes Leicestershire comprises a non-metropolitan county, with seven districts, and the unitary authority area of Leicester.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Leicestershire is generally a lowland county, characterised by small, rolling hills.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] It is bisected by the River Soar, which rises near the Warwickshire border south of Hinckley and flows north through Leicester and Loughborough before reaching the Trent at the county boundary.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] To the west of the river is Charnwood Forest, an upland area which contains Bardon Hill, which at 278 m (912 ft) is the county's highest point.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] There are prehistoric earthworks in the county, and Leicester was a Roman settlement.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] The region was settled by the Angles in the sixth century and became part of the Kingdom of Mercia, and the county existed at the time of the Domesday Survey in the 1080s.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] The county has had a relatively settled existence; however, it was the site of the Battle of Bosworth Field in 1485, which established the Tudor dynasty's position as monarchs of England.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] During the Industrial Revolution the Leicestershire coalfield in the north and west of the county was exploited.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Leicester became known for shoemaking, and with Loughborough continues to be a manufacturing centre.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] In agriculture the county is known for Stilton cheese and Melton Mowbray pork pies.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] The Domesday Book (1086) records four wapentakes in the territory of Leicestershire: Guthlaxton, Framland, Goscote and Gartree.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] These later became hundreds, with the division of Goscote into West Goscote and East Goscote, and the addition of Sparkenhoe hundred.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] The first recorded use of the county name occurs in 1087 as *Lægrecastrescir*.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Leicestershire's external boundaries have changed little since the Domesday Survey.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] The Measham-Donisthorpe exclave of Derbyshire has been exchanged for the Netherseal area, and the urban expansion of Market Harborough has caused Little Bowden, previously in Northamptonshire to be annexed.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Until 1969, the county's legal name was "Leicester" rather than "Leicestershire", although the latter form was in common usage.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] In legal contexts the county was usually referred to as the "County of Leicester" where necessary to distinguish between the city and the county.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] In 1969 the government formally changed the county's name to "Leicestershire" at the county council's request.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] In 1974, the Local Government Act 1972 abolished the county borough status of Leicester city and the county status of neighbouring Rutland, converting both to administrative districts of Leicestershire.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] These actions were reversed on 1 April 1997, when Rutland and the City of Leicester became unitary authorities.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Rutland became a distinct Ceremonial County once again, although it continues to be policed by Leicestershire Constabulary.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] The symbol of the county council, of the Leicestershire County Cricket Club and of Leicester City FC is a fox.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Tradition regards Leicestershire as the birthplace of fox hunting as it is known today.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Hugo Meynell (1735-1808), who lived in Quorn, has a reputation as the "father of modern fox-hunting".
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Melton Mowbray and Market Harborough have associations with fox hunting, as has neighbouring Rutland.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] The flag of Leicestershire features a fox under an heraldic cinquefoil — both symbols often associated with Leicestershire.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] The flag design, made official in July 2021, was the last one registered for an historic county of England.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] The River Soar together with its tributaries and canalisations constitutes the principal river basin of the county, although the River Avon and River Welland through Harborough and along the county's southern boundaries are also significant.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] The Soar rises between Hinckley and Lutterworth, towards the south of the county near the Warwickshire border, and flows northwards, bisecting the county along its north–south axis, through 'Greater' Leicester and then to the east of Loughborough where its course within the county comes to an end.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] It continues north marking the boundary with Nottinghamshire in the borough of Rushcliffe for some 10 kilometres (6.2 mi) before joining the River Trent at the point where Derbyshire, Leicestershire and Nottinghamshire meet.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] The geographical centre of England is in Leicestershire, near Fenny Drayton in the southwest of the county.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] In 2013, the Ordnance Survey calculated that the point was on land at Lindley Hall Farm.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] An alternative point at Meriden, around 10 miles (16 km) to the southwest, had been considered the traditional centre for more than 500 years.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] A large part of the north-west of the county, around Coalville, forms part of the new National Forest area extending into Derbyshire and Staffordshire.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] The highest point of the county is Bardon Hill at 278 m (912 ft), which is also a Marilyn; with other hilly/upland areas of around 150–200 metres (490–660 ft) and above in nearby Charnwood Forest and also to the east of the county around Launde Abbey.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] The lowest point, at an altitude of about 20 metres (66 ft), is located at the county's northernmost tip close to Bottesford where the River Devon flowing through the Vale of Belvoir leaves Leicestershire and enters Nottinghamshire.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] The population of Leicestershire (excluding Leicester Unitary Authority) is 609,578 people (2001 census).
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] The county covers an area of 2,084 km2 (805 sq mi).
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Its largest population centre is the city of Leicester, followed by the town of Loughborough.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Other large towns include Ashby-de-la-Zouch, Coalville, Hinckley, Lutterworth, Market Harborough, Melton Mowbray, Oadby, Shepshed and Wigston.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Some of the larger of villages are: Burbage (population estimated around 16,500 in 2014), Birstall (population 11,400 in 2004), Broughton Astley, Castle Donington, Kibworth Beauchamp (along with Kibworth Harcourt), Great Glen, Ibstock, Countesthorpe and Kegworth.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] One of the most rapidly expanding villages is Anstey, which has seen expansion in almost every decade since the 1950s to the 2020s, with further expansion expected. .
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Engineering has long been an important part of the economy of Leicestershire.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] John Taylor Bellfounders continues a history of bellfounding in Loughborough since the 14th century.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] In 1881 John Taylors cast the largest bell in Britain, "Great Paul", for St Paul's Cathedral in London.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Norman & Underwood have been making sand cast sheet lead roofing and stained glass since 1825 working on many of England's major cathedrals and historic buildings, including Salisbury Cathedral, Windsor Castle, Westminster Abbey, Hampton Court Palace, and Chatsworth House.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] There were three coal mines that operated in Coalville from the 1820s until 1986.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Abbey Pumping Station houses four enormous steam powered beam engines built in Leicester in the 1890s in the Vulcan factory owned by Josiah Gimson, whose son Ernest Gimson was an influential furniture designer and architect of the English Arts and Crafts movement.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] The business relocated to an 18-acre site in 1926.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] In the 1950s, 60s and 70s they were employing over 1,400 people to meet demand.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] In 1969, 1978 and in 1994 the business won the prestigious Queen's Award for Enterprise.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] In 2006 Universal Conveyors was acquired and in 2007 Phoenix Parker Holdings Ltd was formed.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] In 2014 Phoenix Transworld, Cartem & Universal Conveyors marketed under the Parker brand.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Aggregate Industries UK (construction materials), Infotec in Ashby-de-la-Zouch (electronic information display boards), Alstec in Whetstone, Leicestershire (airport baggage handling systems), and Brush Traction (railway locomotives) in Loughborough.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] There are also consultancies (including Pick Everard) in Leicestershire supporting engineering and the built environment.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Local commitment to nurturing the upcoming cadre of British engineers includes apprenticeship schemes with local companies, and academic-industrial connections with the engineering departments at Leicester University, De Montfort University and Loughborough University.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] The Engineering Innovation Centre and Centre for Excellence for low carbon and fuel cell technologies are both based at Loughborough University.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Private sector research and development organisations include PERA—the technology based consultancy in Melton Mowbray, and MIRA—the automotive research and development centre based on the outskirts of Hinckley.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Automotive and aerospace engineers use the test facilities at Mallory Park, and Bruntingthorpe Aerodrome and proving ground.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] On 18 October 2007, the last airworthy Avro Vulcan was flown from Bruntingthorpe Aerodrome after 10 years of restoration there by aerospace engineers of the Vulcan Operating Company.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Leicestershire has a long history of livestock farming which continues today.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Robert Bakewell (1725–1795) of Dishley, near Loughborough, was a revolutionary in the field of selective breeding.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Bakewell's Leicester Longwool sheep was much prized by farmers across the British Empire and is today a heritage breed admired.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Commercial and rare breeds associated with the descendants of Bakewell's sheep include the English Leicester, Border Leicester, Bluefaced Leicester, Scotch mule and Welsh halfbred.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] The Leicestershire County Show is held on the first Bank Holiday in May each year and includes animal showings, trade exhibitions and show jumping.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Melton Mowbray Market is an important regional livestock market.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Field sports remain an important part of the rural economy of Leicestershire, with stables, kennels and gunsmiths based in the county.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Stilton and Red Leicester cheeses and the pork pie are the three most famous contributions to English cuisine from Leicestershire.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Leicestershire food producers include Claybrooke mill, one of the very few commercially working watermills left in Britain producing a range of over 40 flours; meat from rare and minority breeds from Brockleby's Pies; and Christmas turkey and goose from Seldom Seen Farm.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Two dairies produce Red Leicester cheese in the county: Long Clawson, who also produce blue stilton, and the Leicestershire Handmade Cheese Company.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] All-natural non-alcoholic fruit cordials and pressed drinks are made by Belvoir Fruit Farms and sold in supermarkets across Britain.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Swithland Spring Water is sourced from the Charnwood hills.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Breweries in Leicestershire and Rutland are listed on the Leicester CAMRA website.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] The county's largest beer brewer is Everards, and there are several microbreweries.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Various markets are held across the county.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Leicester Market, given its Market status in the 13th century, is said to be the largest outdoor covered marketplace in Europe and among the products on sale are fruit and vegetables sold by market stallholders, and fresh fish and meat in the Indoor Market.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] The annual East Midlands Food & Drink Festival held in Melton Mowbray had over 200 exhibitors and 20,000 visitors attending in 2007 making it the largest British regional food festival.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Food processing in the city and county includes popular British fish and chip shop pie Pukka Pies who are based in Syston.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Walkers Midshire Foods, part of the Samworth Brothers group, makes sausages and pies in its Beaumont Leys factories.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Walkers Midshire Foods - Walkers Deli & Sausage Co, part of Samworth Brothers is on the Cobden Street Industrial Estate in Belgrave.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] The Business specialises in the manufacturing of Premium Sliced Cooked Meats and Sausages as well as being the largest producer of Pate in the UK.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Samworth Brothers has operations in Leicestershire and Cornwall (Ginsters), making a range of products from sandwiches to desserts for UK retailers under their brands as well the company's own portfolio of brands including Dickinson & Morris, producers of pork pies and Melton Hunt Cake.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Walkers crisps are made in Beaumont Leys using Lincolnshire potatoes.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] United Biscuits have their distribution centre in Ashby-de-la-Zouch as well as a snacks factory and they also have a biscuit factory in Wigston.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] The Masterfoods UK factory at Melton Mowbray produces petfood.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Hand made chocolates are produced by Chocolate Perfection in Ashby-de-la-Zouch.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Some 15 major Indian food manufacturers are based in Leicester including Sara Foods, Mayur Foods, Cofresh Snack Foods Ltd, Farsan, Apni Roti and Spice n Tice.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] The 'Mithai' Indian sweet market is catered for by award-winning Indian restaurants—for instance, the vegetable samosas approved by the Vegetarian Society sold at The Sharmilee on Belgrave Road AKA the Golden Mile in the Belgrave area of Leicester.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] The growing market for Indian food has afforded new opportunities to long-standing local companies, for example the Long Clawson dairy, a co-operative manufacturer of Stilton (cheese) now also makes Paneer cheese used in the Indian dish Mattar Paneer.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Leicestershire food exported abroad includes cheese from the Long Clawson dairy, which is sold in supermarkets in Canada and the United States via a network of distributors coordinated by Taunton-based company Somerdale.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Belvoir Fruit Farms cordials and pressé drinks are sold on the United States east coast in Wegmans Food Markets, World Market, Harris Teeter, Dean & DeLuca, and in specialised British food stores such as Myers of Keswick (New York City) and the British Pantry (near Washington, D.C.).
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Leicester and Leicestershire has had a traditional industry of knitwear, hosiery and footwear, and the sheep on the county's coat of arms is recognition of this.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Cheaper global competition, coupled with the 1999 slump in the UK fashion retail sector, led to the end of much of the cheaper clothing manufacturing industry.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Today Leicestershire companies focus on high quality clothing and speciality textiles.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Other local companies manufacture knitwear such as Commando Knitwear of Wigston, and others specialise in technical textiles for industrial or medical purposes.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Clothing and fabric for the British Asian community is made here—for example the shop Saree Mandir sells silk sarees and salwar suits for women whose design patterns closely follow contemporary Indian trends.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] The Knitting Industries' Federation continues to be based in Leicestershire.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] On the creative side the design centre for next is headquartered in Enderby, and the design centre for George Clothing (Asda/Walmart) is in Lutterworth.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] De Montfort University has, in the form of its Fashion and Contour Design course a leading design department for female underwear.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] It also has the only UK University courses in Footwear Design providing future designers for local shoemakers Shoefayre, Stead and Simpson, and Shoe Zone, who all have their headquarters in the county.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Belgrave-based British United Shoe Machinery, part of a group which for most of the 20th century was the world's largest manufacturer of footwear machinery and materials, exporting shoe machinery to more than 50 countries.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] In the 1960s and 1970s it was Leicester's biggest employer, employing more than 4,500 locally and 9,500 worldwide.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] The company had "a respected reputation for technical innovation and excellence", between 1898 and 1960 it developed and marketed nearly 800 new and improved shoe machines and patented more than 9,000 inventions, at one time employing 5% of the UK’s patent agents.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Also Belgrave-based Wolsey, a heritage British clothing brand founded in 1755, making it one of the oldest existing textile companies in the world.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Fred Perry also had a Factory in Belgrave.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] University Hospitals Leicester NHS Trust employs around 11,000 at its three hospitals in the city and county, the Glenfield, the General and the Royal Infirmary.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Leicestershire Partnership NHS Trust employs over 5,500 staff providing mental health, learning disability and community health services in the city and county.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] These services are commissioned by the three Clinical Commissioning Groups, led by local GPs.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] The British Psychological Society, the Institution of Occupational Safety and Health (IOSH) based in Wigston, and the National Examination Board in Occupational Safety and Health (NEBOSH) have their head offices in Leicestershire.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Pharmaceutical, biotechnology and medical instrument manufacturing companies include 3M, Bridgehead International in Melton, Fisher Scientific in Loughborough, and Ashfield Healthcare in Ashby-de-la-Zouch.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] East Midlands Airport is one mile (1.6 km) south of Castle Donington, next to the M1 in north-west Leicestershire, and is the second largest freight airport in the United Kingdom after London Heathrow.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] DHL Aviation have a large purpose-built facility at EMA, and courier companies UPS and TNT also use the airport as a base.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Lufthansa Cargo is also a regular user of East Midlands, and the airport is a primary hub for Royal Mail.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] The M1 is Leicestershire's other important transport hub.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] The start of the M6, and part of the A14 briefly intersect with the southern tip of Leicestershire.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Many large retail companies have huge warehouses at the Magna Park complex near Lutterworth.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] The Widdowson Group make use of J21a of the M1 to provide warehousing, transportation, freight forwarding, garage services and LGV/HGV training.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Pall-Ex of Ellistown provide automated palletised freight distribution services from their location off Junction 22 of the M1.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] The Midland Main Line provides important connections to Yorkshire and London, and the Birmingham–Stansted Line is essentially Leicestershire's east–west connection from Hinckley to Melton.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Ibstock-based developer Wilson Bowden was bought in 2007 by Barratt Developments plc in a £2.2 billion deal.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Charles Street Buildings (Leicester) and Jelson Homes are two other successful Leicester-based property companies.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Hamilton-based Sofidel Group manufactures more than 600 million toilet rolls and kitchen towel rolls per year in its Leicestershire factories.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Toy car company Corgi have their European operation at the Meridian Business Park, although the toys are now manufactured in China and the company is owned by Margate-based Hornby.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Leicestershire is twinned with Kilkenny, Ireland.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Leicester's Cultural Quarter is an ambitious plan to drive the regeneration of a large run-down area of the city.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] It has delivered: a new venue for the performing arts, Curve; creative workspaces for artists and designers, LCB Depot; and a Digital Media Centre.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Many creative and media businesses have thrived in the region.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] As part of a 2002 marketing campaign, the plant conservation charity Plantlife chose the foxglove as the county flower.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Financial and business service companies with operations in Leicestershire include Alliance & Leicester, Cambridge & Counties Bank, Royal Bank of Scotland, State Bank of India, HSBC and PricewaterhouseCoopers.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Pension provision company Mattioli Woods employs 170 people at its Grove Park, Enderby, HQ and has a reputation for employing graduates directly from Leicestershire Universities.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Companies that have their head office in the area include Next and British Gas Business.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] The European Association of Trade Mark Owners and the Point of Purchase Advertising International (POPAI) are based in Leicestershire.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Key stakeholders promoting economic development formed Leicester & Leicestershire Economic Partnership in 2011.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Leicestershire Chamber of Commerce is another good source for business advice.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] The Leicestershire Business Awards has categories including Investing in Leicestershire, Contribution to the Community, and Entrepreneur of the Year.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Recent Leicestershire winners of the Queen's Award for Enterprise are listed on the Lord Lieutenant's website.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] This is a chart of trend of regional gross value added of the non-metropolitan county of Leicestershire and Rutland (it does not include the City of Leicester) at current basic prices published (pp.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] 240–253) by *Office for National Statistics* with figures in millions of British Pounds Sterling.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] For lieutenancy purposes, Leicestershire consists of the non-metropolitan county and the City of Leicester.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] For administrative purposes, most of the county is run by the Leicestershire County Council, though the City of Leicester is run independently by the Leicester City Council.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] The non-metropolitan county is divided into seven districts ran by district councils: The seven district councils in Leicestershire are Blaby, Charnwood, Harborough, Hinckley & Bosworth, Melton, North West Leicestershire and Oadby & Wigston.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] It has been proposed by the Leicestershire County Council in 2018 to get rid of the district councils.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Leicestershire County Council consists of 55 elected members, from 52 wards.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] The most recent election was the May 2017 elections, where all seats were up for re-election.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Following these elections the current political composition of the council is 42 Conservatives, 9 Liberal Democrats and 4 Labour councillors.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] County Hall, in Glenfield, some 3 miles (4.8 km) north-west of central Leicester and a little over 4 miles (6.4 km) from Leicester railway station, is the seat of Leicestershire County Council and the headquarters of the county authority.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Below the County Council, there are seven district councils, Blaby, Charnwood, Harborough, Hinckley and Bosworth, Melton, North West Leicestershire and Oadby and Wigston.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] The City of Leicester is a unitary authority which is separate from the county for local government, and provides all services in its area; the City Council meets at Leicester Town Hall.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] As of 2026, there are three rival proposals for local government in Leicestershire to be reorganised into either two or three unitary authorities.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Outside of Leicester (which would remain unchanged or expanded) the proposals would see the current structure of the county council and seven districts abolished.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Government consultation on these three proposals ran from 5 February 2026 to 26 March 2026.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Following the 2024 general election, Leicestershire is represented by eleven members of parliament (MPs).
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Labour Party won three seats within the City of Leicester in 2019, but ended up losing two, Leicester East was won by Conservative and Leicester South was won by an Independent politician.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Labour however gained two seats back in Leicestershire from the Conservatives in Loughborough and North West Leicestershire.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] The other six Leicestershire seats are represented by Conservative MPs.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Publicly funded secondary schools in Leicestershire are comprehensive.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] The schools are segregated by age in some areas to ages 10–14 (middle schools), and 14–16 (upper schools) or 14–18 (upper schools which also provide sixth-form education).
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] The schools, compared with other LEAs, have large numbers on the roll with school enrolment often 2,000 and more.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] For Melton and Blaby districts, although there is division by middle and upper schools, there is only one upper school in either district, giving no choice of school.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] However, many students of Lutterworth College in Harborough District actually hail from Blaby district.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Charnwood has the largest school population—four times the size of the Melton district.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] In 2007, the best-performing state school at GCSE was Beauchamp College in Oadby.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] No comprehensives in Leicestershire LEA were rated as poor performers, unlike in some neighbouring counties.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] For A-levels, the best comprehensive school in the county was the De Lisle College in Loughborough.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] The best schools overall at A-level were the two private single-sex schools in Loughborough—Loughborough Grammar School and Loughborough High School.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Percentage of pupils gaining 5 grades A–C in 2007 including English and Maths (46.8% was the England average compared to Leicestershire's 48.9%).
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Loughborough Amherst School (formerly Our Lady's Convent School) was a co-educational day and boarding school located in Loughborough.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] It closed at the end of the 2024–25 academic year, following financial hardship.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] There are four general further education colleges operating in Leicestershire; Leicester College, Loughborough College, South Leicestershire College and Stephenson College.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] All offer various vocational courses as well as apprenticeships and some academic courses.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Brooksby Melton College provides apprenticeships and further education training courses in animal care, countryside, equine, fisheries and land-based service engineering, at their Brooksby campus.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Leicestershire has three universities, the University of Leicester, Loughborough University and De Montfort University.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] The full range of music is performed in the county, from early medieval, European and Asian classical music, folk, jazz, blues, rock and pop.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Download Festival, a major hard rock and metal festival, is hosted at Donington Park and 110 Above Festival takes place in the north west of the county near to Twycross.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] The Leicester Symphony Orchestra and the Leicestershire Schools Symphony Orchestra are two of the larger orchestras based in the county.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] The Philharmonia Orchestra, though based in London, holds annual residencies in Leicester.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Amateur orchestras include the Leicestershire Sinfonia, Loughborough Orchestra, Charnwood Orchestra, Coalville Light Orchestra and Soar Valley Music Centre Orchestra.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] The Longsdale Consort perform music of the renaissance and baroque periods.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Stores selling sheet music and musical instruments in Leicestershire include Music Junkie Ltd, Sona Rupa (Indian), Intasound Music Ltd and MH Music (MH Music are actually in the centre of Market Harborough).
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] The county is served by BBC East Midlands and ITV Central (East) television regions, with television signals received from the Waltham transmitting station.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] The BBC local radio station is BBC Radio Leicester, broadcast from studios in Leicester.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] Local commercial radio stations serving the county are Capital Midlands, Greatest Hits Radio Midlands, Smooth East Midlands and Hits Radio East Midlands.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/leicestershire] The community radio stations are Demon FM in Leicester; The Eye serving Melton Mowbray and the Vale of Belvoir; Harborough FM in Market Harborough; and Cross Counties Radio serving Lutterworth.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough] The hospice, which is located in Loughborough, Leicestershire is a purpose designed and built children's hospice.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough] The current main unit has fourteen beds, many of which are pre-bookable, and two are available at short notice for emergency care.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough] This facility was founded by Gail and Harry Moore, in celebration of their daughter, Laura, who had died of Leukaemia in 1989 despite three years of treatment and a donation of bone marrow from her twin brother Kit.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough] Rainbows was officially opened by Charles, Prince of Wales, then The Prince of Wales in April 1995.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough] It was named Rainbows because Laura saw a beautiful and complete rainbow as the family were driving over the Pennine hills in Yorkshire on their way to Leicestershire.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough] They saw the rainbow as a symbol of hope, even in death.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough] It provides services throughout the East Midlands.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough] It is almost entirely funded through voluntary sources.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough] Harry and Gail Moore also founded the charity COPE to build a children's cancer unit at the Leicester Royal Infirmary and The Laura Centre - a bereavement counseling service for those affected by the death of a child and for bereaved children.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough] Harry Moore also wrote of his experiences in one of his books *A Lark Ascending*.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough] Harry was initially the chairman of the charity and then became CEO part time for two years to help grow the hospice.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough] He now works in an occasional advisory capacity as well as managing his international management consultancy business.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough] His wife Gail is currently the Income Development Director for The Laura Centre.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough] This care is provided by a team of nurses, carers and therapists, supported by a group of administrators and fund-raisers, and all of this is under the direction of a team of specialist doctors providing, paediatric and palliative care.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough] Rainbow’s offer services to the whole family, to discuss a child’s impending death, and to help with practical matters.
[src:rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough/rainbows-children-s-hospice-loughborough] This support is individually tailored to each family's needs to meet their culture and religious beliefs.
